,'',0),(86,1,'2013-11-06 20:56:19','2013-11-06 20:56:19','<p dir=\"ltr\">my vision is to photograph the great himalayan peaks of the world and convey the feeling of standing in their presence.  in the largest sizes i can.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">the inspiration came some time back, when i lost a good friend and realized that the time had come to do those things i had always said i would do someday.  first on that list was traveling to to himalayas, in particular k2 in northern pakistan, the 2nd tallest mountain in the world.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">i was pretty concerned about visiting pakistan, so decided first to try my hand with altitude in the somewhat mellower country of nepal.  this was in 2008 , when i made the trek around dhaulagiri, seventh tallest.  i have since returned to nepal 3 more times to explore and photograph the incredible mountains here and enjoy the impeccable hospitality of the people.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">in 2011 i f felt seasoned enough to try pakistan - inspired by friends who had been and had wonderful things to say - so in a sort of life crossroads i bought a plane ticket to islamabad to join an expedition to the baltoro glacier and the foot of k2.  this was a dream 10 years in the making, and my original mountain valhalla, for which i was willing to stick my neck out a little.  for k2 and it\'s surroundings are places that have inspired me like no other - not only for their singular architecture and impressively bold form, but for the inspiration taken from the stories written in human struggle to climb them, k2 in particular, the \"mountain of mountains\".  in books and photos they have captured my imagination for as long as i can remember.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">there is a spirituality to these places for me - and i think that as a photographer knowing what to shoot is as important as knowing how to shoot - the vision.  in the himalayas i am able to find this &amp; synergize 2 of my  passions - the most beautiful mountains in the world and photography.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">doug k</p>\r\n\r\n<div><a title=\"The Gallery\" href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/gallery/\">View the Gallery</a></div>','<span class=\"small\">About</span><br />Doug Kofsky','','publish','open','open','','about-doug-kofsky','','','2013-12-20 02:51:43','2013-12-20 02:51:43','',0,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?page_id=86',0,'page','',0),(87,1,'2013-11-06 20:56:19','2013-11-06 20:56:19','Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Vivamus dignissim ac erat id interdum. Curabitur scelerisque, urna a consectetur vestibulum, nibh odio molestie tellus, in sollicitudin sapien nulla ut nisi. Ut id sapien suscipit, tincidunt dui ut, gravida metus. Sed eleifend sem eget luctus malesuada. Mauris vitae euismod sapien. Sed eleifend nisi sem, sit amet suscipit mauris varius sed. Maecenas laoreet nibh at imperdiet imperdiet. Proin malesuada aliquam metus vitae tempor. Etiam accumsan ante sapien, ut pretium sapien elementum nec. Phasellus non rutrum libero. Nulla commodo elementum massa eu tempus. Nulla tincidunt venenatis quam. Donec ornare eros nec ultrices porta. Vestibulum non lectus dolor. Nulla ullamcorper auctor euismod. Sed non placerat turpis. Donec at metus eget lectus aliquam tempus auctor sed metus. Fusce dolor dolor, pellentesque vitae vestibulum at, malesuada et dolor. Maecenas eu nibh vestibulum, posuere ligula eget, interdum massa. Sed porttitor cursus nunc.','About Doug Kofsky','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2013-11-06 20:56:19','2013-11-06 20:56:19','',86,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(88,1,'2013-11-06 20:56:35','2013-11-06 20:56:35','The 14 tallest mountains in the world are located in Nepal, Pakistan and Tibet.  i have now visited nepal on 4 occasions.  pakistan i have visited once.  tibet i have yet to see.\r\n\r\n<strong>Nepal</strong>\r\n\r\nNepal is the hub of  himalayan tourism, a hindu/buddhist amalgam of contradiction &amp; ancient culture and home to 9 of the 14, including mount everest.   many national parks have been established within nepal for trekking tourism, and there are among the locals some of the most hospitable hosts and indomitable guides in the world.  villages are intersperse all over the hills, covered with jungle in the lowland and then soaring up impossibly to the north, a great white barrier across the sky, the name of which tranlates to \"the abode of snow\" or \"where the snow is.  this is the place to start for anyone who wants to see giant mountains.  what you see here is life changing - and best of all nepal is relatively unrestricted &amp; open for business - so with a pile of rupees in your hand &amp; a good pair of boots, you can go just about anywhere.  cheers to that.\r\n\r\nin nepal i trek part of the time solo in order to really feel lost.  other times i put a crew together of 2 guys to help me get even more off the beaten path.  we\'ve had some great adventures and found some new photo terrain as well as visits from the hindu goddess saraswati, goddess of learning.  for it is more different in culture, smell, outlook, horizon, division, morality - in every way it defies description.  b\r\n\r\n<strong>Pakistan</strong>\r\n\r\nPakistan - the level of apprehension even at the name for americans now is steadily escalating, and the chances of feeling safe to return there have never been lower.  such a waste, for i loved just so much about pakistan - so many cool people -good, honest, intelligent people - present, not scamming you, open to real discussion, sad over the loss of frendship between the governments of our countries.   I am very lucky -  we had no problems on our trip whatsoever.  i met some wonderful guys &amp; pray we can turn it around.\r\n\r\nthe geography of northern pakistan is completely different.  unlike the jungles of nepal, the terrain here is scoured by a dry wind, all brown hues, and scorchingly dry.  the himalayan range peters out to the west on the flanks of a mountain named nanga parbat, and further travel north leads to another mighty range, the karakoram range - with dimensions attaining similar magnitude in scale.  I was very lucky  to trek the baltoro glacier at least once, and photograph “the throne room of the mountain gods.”  The scale and architecture of these peaks is on another level - and the weather pattern in the karakoram is very different than the himalaya - with larger glaciers &amp; more instability.  for 15 days we drank water stained brown with the silty dust that rains off this similarly colored landscape.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"> </span>','The Location','','publish','open','open','','the-location','','','2013-12-20 03:13:00','2013-12-20 03:13:00','',0,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?page_id=88',0,'page','',0),(89,1,'2013-11-06 20:56:35','2013-11-06 20:56:35','Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Vivamus dignissim ac erat id interdum. Curabitur scelerisque, urna a consectetur vestibulum, nibh odio molestie tellus, in sollicitudin sapien nulla ut nisi. Ut id sapien suscipit, tincidunt dui ut, gravida metus. Sed eleifend sem eget luctus malesuada. Mauris vitae euismod sapien. Sed eleifend nisi sem, sit amet suscipit mauris varius sed. Maecenas laoreet nibh at imperdiet imperdiet. Proin malesuada aliquam metus vitae tempor. Etiam accumsan ante sapien, ut pretium sapien elementum nec. Phasellus non rutrum libero. Nulla commodo elementum massa eu tempus. Nulla tincidunt venenatis quam. Donec ornare eros nec ultrices porta. Vestibulum non lectus dolor. Nulla ullamcorper auctor euismod. Sed non placerat turpis. Donec at metus eget lectus aliquam tempus auctor sed metus. Fusce dolor dolor, pellentesque vitae vestibulum at, malesuada et dolor. Maecenas eu nibh vestibulum, posuere ligula eget, interdum massa. Sed porttitor cursus nunc.','The Location','','inherit','open','open','','88-revision-v1','','','2013-11-06 20:56:35','2013-11-06 20:56:35','',88,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/88-re