e yet to see.</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Nepal</span></strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Nepal is the hub of  himalayan tourism, a hindu/buddhist amalgam of contradiction &amp; ancient culture.   many national parks are demarcated within nepal for trekking tourism, and there are among the locals some of the most hospitable hosts and indomitable guides in the world.  truly at present a mecca for anyone who wants to see giant mountains.  tourist inflation is soaring, as globalisation adjusts prices to near western levels in tourist hotspots, here in what is known as the 3rd poorest country in the world. But what you see here cannot help but change you.  Just everything is different.  And in a beautiful way. Nepal is open for true adventure - the feeling that with a pile of rupees in your hand &amp; a good pair of boots, you can go just about anywhere.  cheers to that.</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Pakistan</span></strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Pakistan - the level of apprehension even at the name for americans now is steadily escalating, and the perception of that country has never been lower.  I am very lucky - I was able to visit in a period of stability during the summer of 2011 - my dream was to see k2 and surrounds, and i had put it off as too risky, again and again, only to be able to take the plunge after a rought episode at work prompted a personal spell of recklessness - when i bought a plane ticket.  best decision of my life - i loved so much about pakistan - so many cool people - good, honest, intelligent people  - present, not scamming you, open to real discussion, sad over the loss of friendship between our countries.  i met some wonderful guys &amp; pray we can turn it around.</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong> In northern pakistan the himalayas end on the flanks of a mountain named nanga parbat.  another mountain range lies to the north of here, the karakoram range - with dimensions attaining similar magnitude in scale.  I was blessed to trek the baltoro glacier at least once, and photograph “the throne room of the mountain gods.”  The scale and architecture of these peaks is on another level - and the weather pattern in the karakoram is very different than the himalaya - with larger glaciers &amp; more instability.  for 15 days we drank water stained brown with the silty dust that rains off this similarly colored landscape.</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"> </span>','The Location','','inherit','open','open','','88-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-18 14:46:18','2013-12-18 14:46:18','',88,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/88-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(117,1,'2013-11-07 17:49:05','2013-11-07 17:49:05','Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Vivamus dignissim ac erat id interdum. Curabitur scelerisque, urna a consectetur vestibulum, nibh odio molestie tellus, in sollicitudin sapien nulla ut nisi. Ut id sapien suscipit, tincidunt dui ut, gravida metus. Sed eleifend sem eget luctus malesuada. Mauris vitae euismod sapien. Sed eleifend nisi sem, sit amet suscipit mauris varius sed. Maecenas laoreet nibh at imperdiet imperdiet. Proin malesuada aliquam metus vitae tempor. Etiam accumsan ante sapien, ut pretium sapien elementum nec. Phasellus non rutrum libero.\r\n\r\nNulla commodo elementum massa eu tempus. Nulla tincidunt venenatis quam. Donec ornare eros nec ultrices porta. Vestibulum non lectus dolor. Nulla ullamcorper auctor euismod. Sed non placerat turpis. Donec at metus eget lectus aliquam tempus auctor sed metus. Fusce dolor dolor, pellentesque vitae vestibulum at, malesuada et dolor. Maecenas eu nibh vestibulum, posuere ligula eget, interdum massa. Sed porttitor cursus nunc.\r\n<h2>A Section Title</h2>\r\nNulla tincidunt venenatis