013-11-22 20:39:29','2013-11-22 20:39:29','[justified_image_grid preset=3 row_height=300 height_deviation=40 caption=fade min_height=600 orderby=menu_order last_row=flexible disable_cropping=yes developer_link=hide load_more=scroll load_more_limit=6 recent_posts=yes recents_post_type=product]','Doug Kofsky<br />M O U N T A I N S C A P E S','','inherit','open','open','','38-revision-v1','','','2013-11-22 20:39:29','2013-11-22 20:39:29','',38,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/38-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(238,2,'2013-11-23 02:26:08','2013-11-23 02:26:08','<p dir=\"ltr\">With the digital era photography has risen like a phoenix from it’s own ashes.  there is a level of control for the photographer (and especially the home photographer) previously unknown in the art.  From photoshop, photomerging, rgb printers, high sensitivity sensors, lens stabilization -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When my photography heroes came to the himalaya before me, they shot on film, and the earliest shot with tripods -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">vittorio sella came up the baltoro in 1909 with the duke of abruzzi and really introduced these mountains to the world - some of his photography here</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.panopticongallery.com/artist/vittorio_sella/#Vittorio_Sella_29.jpg\">http://www.panopticongallery.com/artist/vittorio_sella/#Vittorio_Sella_29.jpg</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">for american nature photographers ansel adams is the photographer to which all others seem a footnote - &amp; to his credit, his technique is very democratic, the zone system outlined in his masterpiece book “the negative” being the foundation upon which my photography is based.  as a man of his time, he shot with a large format camera &amp; a tripod, and of course the results speak for themselves</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ansel_Adams\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ansel_Adams</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">a photographer seminal to photographing just the himalayas is shiro shirahata.  his 2 folio books “nepal himalaya” &amp; “karakoram” begin to see the mountains themselves as characters - his books are portrait albums of the tallest mountains on earth.  his style represents the height of expedition style - on his treks he brought armies of porters, they hunted game, carried a large format camera &amp; a tripod.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html\">http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">galen rowell i see as an evolution to “alpine style”.  his tool of choice was the nikkor 20 mm f4 on a 35mm dslr - in other words, he could handhold the smaller, lighter, wide lensed camera, and get himself just about anywhere - a great climber in his own right with that camera.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html\">http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">just as the early siege expeditions to climb the great peaks have evolved to more lightweight attempts, we can see here that mountain photography has now paralleled that evolution through “alpine style” to what is now called “ultralight”.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">lens stabilization and the high sensitivities obtainable by digital sensors have made it possible now to shoot without a tripod - a seriously clunky encumbrance on uneven terrain in the mountains.  a cart full of giant photo plates has evolved to a backpack full of xray sensitive film cartridges and is now solid state media cards that you can slip in your pocket.  And everything has to get safely back from asia.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">shirahata - the culmination of expedition style</p>\r\n<b><b>\r\n\r\n</b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">rowell - the dawn of alpine style and the nikkor 20 mm - evolution - but still carried film</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop.  rgb printers.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">the process - photoshopping &amp; photomerging - taking multiple photographs - high sensitivity sensors &amp; handheld - lens stabilizationthe images are merged - the advantage being that you can them make them pretty big as the combined effect makes for a massive image able</p>\r\n<b><b>\r\n\r\n</b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photography “alpine style”</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">baryta paper - baryllium - testing - laboriously profiled</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">homemade - hand signed (image)</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">gear i have used that has made a difference</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon eos rebel t1i</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 15 - 85 mm is usm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 18 - 200 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nikkor 50 mm f1.2</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon 6d</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 24 -105 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 70 -200 mm t4</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brunton 26w solar charger</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">schneider polarizer</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop cs4 &amp; cs5</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ipf 6300 print plugin for photoshop</p>\r\n<b><b>\r\n\r\n\r\n</b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">about sizing</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">i have unlimited editions of everything in their folio size -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">for larger blah blah limited editions</p>\r\n<b><b>\r\n\r\n</b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">if you can dream it - i might be able to print it!  feel free to inquire about custom sizing over and above the x - large size!  some of them go even bigger...</p>','The Process','','inherit','open','open','','125-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 02:26:08','2013-11-23 02:26:08','',125,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/125-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(240,2,'2013-11-23 02:28:45','2013-11-23 02:28:45','<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/the-location/doug_and_valley/#main\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-118\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-118\" alt=\"doug_and_valley\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/doug_and_valley.jpg\" width=\"537\" height=\"357\" /></a>hard to know where to start to quantify my experience of the cross cultural adventures undertaken to put myself in position - none of it could have been done without the excellent professional services of local guides in the respective countries of nepal and pakistan.\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">within their national borders these 2 countries hold 13 of the 14 tallest peaks on earth.  because of logistical considerations i have now visited nepal on 4 occasions &amp; pakistan once.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nepal is the hub of the himalayan tourism destination wheel, a hindu/somewhat buddhist amalgam of contradiction that starts to obtain its own logic only upon closer inspection than the patient can at times be expected to contrive.  everything starts and ends in the city of kathmandu - which once navigated is the final barrier to nirvana.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">many national parks are demarcated within nepal for trekking tourism, and there are among the locals some of the most hospitable hosts and indomitable guides in the world.  truly at present a mecca for anyone who wants to see giant mountains and accompanying culture.  tourist inflation is soaring, as globalisation adjusts prices to near western levels in tourist hotspots, in the 3rd poorest country in the world.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">But what you see here cannot help but change you.  Just everything is different.  And in a beautiful way, Nepal is so open to adventure - the feeling that with a pile of rupees in your hand &amp; a good pair of boots, you can go just about anywhere.  cheers to that.</p>\r\n<b><b>\r\n\r\n</b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Pakistan was a different case - the level of apprehension even at the name for americans now is steadily escalating, and the perception of that country has never been lower.  I am very lucky - I was able to visit in a period of stability during the summer of 2011 - i had put it off &amp; put it off, only to be able to take the plunge after a rought episode at work prompted a personal spell of recklessness - when i bought a plane ticket.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">best decision of my life - i loved every minute of pakistan, even when i was bitching:)  people there were so cool - present, not scamming you, open to real discussion, sad over the loss of friendship between our countries.  i met some wonderful guys &amp; pray we can turn it around.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In northern pakistan the himalayas end on the flanks of a mountain named nanga parbat.  another mountain range lies to the north of here, the karakoram range - with dimensions attaining similar magnitude in scale.  I was blessed to trek the baltoro glacier at least once, and photograph “the throne room of the mountain gods.”  The scale and architecture of these peaks is on another level - and the weather pattern in the karakoram is very different than the himalaya - with larger glaciers &amp; more instability.  for 15 days we drank water stained brown with the silty dust that rains off this similarly colored landscape.</p>\r\n<b><b>\r\n\r\n\r\n</b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">himalaya - \"abode of snow\" (sanskrit)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">karakoram - \"black rock\" (turkic)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">himal - \"mountain\" (sanskrit)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">chuli - \"mountain\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">tse - \"mountain\" (tibetan)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">la - \"high pass\" (tibetan)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ri - \"hill\" (tibetan)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">khola - \"river\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">sundar - \"handsome\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">kharka - \"shelter\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">machha - \"fish\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">puchare - \"tail\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brum - \"mountain\" (balti)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">gasher - \"beautiful\" (balti)</p>\r\n<b id=\"docs-internal-guid-612e253c-82c9-e896-89ff-aeca99288257\">masher - \"trigger\" (balti)</b>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2>A Section Title</h2>\r\n&nbsp;','The Location','','inherit','open','open','','88-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 02:28:45','2013-11-23 02:28:45','',88,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/88-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(241,2,'2013-12-20 02:50:51','2013-12-20 02:50:51','<p dir=\"ltr\">my vision is to photograph the great himalayan peaks of the world and convey the feeling of standing in their presence.  in the largest sizes i can.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">the inspiration came some time back, when i lost a good friend and realized that the time had come to do those things i had always said i would do someday.  first on that list was traveling to to himalayas, in particular k2 in northern pakistan, the 2nd tallest mountain in the world.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">i was pretty concerned about visiting pakistan, so decided first to try my hand with altitude in the somewhat mellower country of nepal.  this was in 2008 , when i made the trek around dhaulagiri, seventh tallest.  i have since returned to nepal 3 more times to explore and photograph the incredible mountains here and enjoy the impeccable hospitality of the people.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">in 2011 i f felt seasoned enough to try pakistan - inspired by friends who had been and had wonderful things to say - so in a sort of life crossroads i bought a plane ticket to islamabad to join an expedition to the baltoro glacier and the foot of k2.  this was a dream 10 years in the making, and my original mountain valhalla, for which i was willing to stick my neck out a little.  for k2 and it\'s surroundings are places that have inspired me like no other - not only for their singular architecture and impressively bold form, but for the inspiration taken from the stories written in human struggle to climb them, k2 in particular, the \"mountain of mountains\".  in books and photos they have captured my imagination for as long as i can remember.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">there is a spirituality to these places for me - and i think that as a photographer knowing what to shoot is as important as knowing how to shoot - the vision.  in the himalayas i am able to find this &amp; synergize 2 of my  passions - the most beautiful mountains in the world and photography.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">doug k</p>\n\n<div><a title=\"The Gallery\" href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/gallery/\">View the Gallery</a></div>','<span class=\"small\">About</span><br />Doug Kofsky','','inherit','open','open','','86-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-20 02:50:51','2013-12-20 02:50:51','',86,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/86-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(242,2,'2013-11-23 02:30:54','2013-11-23 02:30:54','<p dir=\"ltr\">Coming to the himalaya was like meeting friends i had heard much about.  Reading of the  struggles in the valleys and on the flanks, in the irrational pursuit to reach  the tops of these great mountains - these stories had inspired such vivid images in my mind, that it followed that i would take the pilgrimage here as a matter of course.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My first journey was around Dhaulagiri in 2008, the seventh tallest mountain in the world.  As suddenly as we approached, newly opened eyes to this foreign landscape, as a photographer, I knew exactly what needed to be done.  I had suddenly seemed to synergize my two great loves- photography &amp; mountains.  That first trip has been followed by 4 more, each journey its own artistic &amp; technical evolution from the last.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My dream is to photograph the great himalayan peaks - the impossible geography of ultimate mountain form.  There are 14 mountains on earth whose tops reach more than 8000 meters above sea level.   with my eyes &amp; camera i have seen &amp; photographed 10 of them.  Around these “sacred” summits lie countless other examples of mountain architecture, in distillations approaching perfection - what i am looking for - the most beautiful mountains in the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<div></div>\r\n<a title=\"The Gallery\" href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/gallery/\">View the Gallery</a>','About Doug Kofsky','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 02:30:54','2013-11-23 02:30:54','',86,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(243,2,'2013-11-23 02:31:54','2013-11-23 02:31:54','<p dir=\"ltr\">Coming to the himalaya was like meeting friends i had heard much about.  Reading of the  struggles in the valleys and on the flanks, in the irrational pursuit to reach  the tops of these great mountains - these stories had inspired such vivid images in my mind, that it followed that i would take the pilgrimage here as a matter of course.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My first journey was around Dhaulagiri in 2008, the seventh tallest mountain in the world.  As suddenly as we approached, newly opened eyes to this foreign landscape, as a photographer, I knew exactly what</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">needed to be done.  I had suddenly seemed to synergize my two great loves- photography &amp; mountains.  That first trip has been followed by 4 more, each journey its own artistic &amp; technical evolution from the last.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My dream is to photograph the great himalayan peaks - the impossible geography of ultimate m</p>\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-112\" alt=\"doug_and_friends\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/doug_and_friends-300x200.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ountain form.  There are 14 mountains on earth whose tops reach more than 8000 meters above sea level.   with my eyes &amp; camera i have seen &amp; photographed 10 of them.  Around these “sacred” summits lie countless other examples of mountain architecture, in distillations approaching perfection - what i am looking for - the most beautiful mountains in the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<div></div>\r\n<a title=\"The Gallery\" href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/gallery/\">View the Gallery</a>','About Doug Kofsky','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 02:31:54','2013-11-23 02:31:54','',86,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(244,2,'2013-12-15 16:01:39','2013-12-15 16:01:39','<strong>makalu-barun national park, nepal</strong>\n\none of the benefits of trekking with a small crew is the logistical freedom to chase the light.  lanmale kharka had been described to me as \"the sound of music meets 7 years in tibet\" - praise indeed, coming from the modern alpinist don bowie.  i decided to try my hand at capturing this idea - &amp; with a short day from makalu basecamp to get down, and the afternoon to scout out the angles, i was ready early in the morning - hoping to find shape among the stone enclosures standing before the mountains of dawn.\n\nof course, as in many cases, when the dawn actually came - my instinct pulled strongly in another direction - GO UP. luckily having recently been above 6000 meters, i was fully acclimated and able to scamper up the hillside above camp - and the result is what you see.  cheers to my korean movie friends who made camping here interesting and satisfying - fun to talk shop about the biz with members of the vibrant korean film community.  also fun to look down from my perch and watch them scampering about below, desperately shooting the golden hour with their cameras.\n\nmerge of 13 photographs – Canon EF 24 -105 mm @ 105mm/f13.  Canon EOS 6D 1/200th second exposure @ ISO 400.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe DNG Converter/Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n<div><a href=\"http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/content/uploads/2013/11/from_langmale_kharka_SAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-186\" alt=\"from_langmale_kharka_SAMPLE\" src=\"http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/content/uploads/2013/11/from_langmale_kharka_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"562\" height=\"396\" /></a></div>\n<div></div>','dawn from langmale kharka','','inherit','open','open','','180-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-15 16:01:39','2013-12-15 16:01:39','',180,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/180-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(245,2,'2013-11-23 03:50:54','2013-11-23 03:50:54','','infopage','','inherit','open','open','','infopage','','','2013-11-23 03:50:54','2013-11-23 03:50:54','',180,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/infopage.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(246,2,'2013-12-02 14:56:13','2013-12-02 14:56:13','<strong>Barun Glacier valley, nepal</strong>\n\nthis is makalu - @ 8481 meters the fifth tallest in the world, soaring above the barun glacier on her southwest flank.\n\nshe is the outlier of some high places indeed, as the eastern anchor of the highest thrust of himalaya there is, with everest and lhotse accompanying her in similar height up the valley to the left.\n\nwhat to be said of makalu basecamp? it\'s as good a place as possible to land a helicopter close to 5000m. It\'s also a good place to observe makalu\'s towering southwest flank. it\'s not a good place for fresh produce or any sustenance beyond the most simple items. Learned that the hard way spending more than a week here and above. when traveling this way one is advised to bring supplemental contingencies for protein &amp; vitamins.\n\nmerge of 16 photographs - Canon EF 24 -105 mm @ 45mm/f22.  Canon EOS 6D 1/50th second exposure @ ISO 250.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe DNG Converter/Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_170\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"565\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/dawn_from_makalu_basecamp_SAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-170 \" alt=\"Detail Sample\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/dawn_from_makalu_basecamp_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"565\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','Dawn From Makalu Basecamp','','inherit','open','open','','169-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-02 14:56:13','2013-12-02 14:56:13','',169,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/169-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(247,2,'2013-11-23 12:34:11','2013-11-23 12:34:11','','infopage2','','inherit','open','open','','infopage2','','','2013-11-23 12:34:11','2013-11-23 12:34:11','',180,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/infopage2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(248,2,'2013-11-23 12:37:21','2013-11-23 12:37:21','','infopage','','inherit','open','open','','infopage-2','','','2013-11-23 12:37:21','2013-11-23 12:37:21','',169,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/infopage1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(250,1,'2013-11-23 18:20:49','2013-11-23 18:20:49','[justified_image_grid preset=3 row_height=300 height_deviation=40 caption=fade min_height=600 orderby=menu_order last_row=flexible disable_cropping=yes developer_link=hide load_more=scroll load_more_limit=6 recent_posts=yes recents_post_type=product]','<span class=\"small\">Doug Kofsky</span><br />Mountainscapes','','inherit','open','open','','38-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 18:20:49','2013-11-23 18:20:49','',38,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/38-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(251,1,'2013-11-23 18:22:25','2013-11-23 18:22:25','<p dir=\"ltr\">Coming to the himalaya was like meeting friends i had heard much about.  Reading of the  struggles in the valleys and on the flanks, in the irrational pursuit to reach  the tops of these great mountains - these stories had inspired such vivid images in my mind, that it followed that i would take the pilgrimage here as a matter of course.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My first journey was around Dhaulagiri in 2008, the seventh tallest mountain in the world.  As suddenly as we approached, newly opened eyes to this foreign landscape, as a photographer, I knew exactly what</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">needed to be done.  I had suddenly seemed to synergize my two great loves- photography &amp; mountains.  That first trip has been followed by 4 more, each journey its own artistic &amp; technical evolution from the last.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My dream is to photograph the great himalayan peaks - the impossible geography of ultimate m</p>\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-112\" alt=\"doug_and_friends\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/doug_and_friends-300x200.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ountain form.  There are 14 mountains on earth whose tops reach more than 8000 meters above sea level.   with my eyes &amp; camera i have seen &amp; photographed 10 of them.  Around these “sacred” summits lie countless other examples of mountain architecture, in distillations approaching perfection - what i am looking for - the most beautiful mountains in the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<div></div>\r\n<a title=\"The Gallery\" href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/gallery/\">View the Gallery</a>','<span class=\"small\">About</span><br />Doug Kofsky','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 18:22:25','2013-11-23 18:22:25','',86,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(252,1,'2013-11-23 18:23:20','2013-11-23 18:23:20','<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/the-location/doug_and_valley/#main\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-118\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-118\" alt=\"doug_and_valley\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/doug_and_valley.jpg\" width=\"537\" height=\"357\" /></a>hard to know where to start to quantify my experience of the cross cultural adventures undertaken to put myself in position - none of it could have been done without the excellent professional services of local guides in the respective countries of nepal and pakistan.\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">within their national borders these 2 countries hold 13 of the 14 tallest peaks on earth.  because of logistical considerations i have now visited nepal on 4 occasions &amp; pakistan once.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nepal is the hub of the himalayan tourism destination wheel, a hindu/somewhat buddhist amalgam of contradiction that starts to obtain its own logic only upon closer inspection than the patient can at times be expected to contrive.  everything starts and ends in the city of kathmandu - which once navigated is the final barrier to nirvana.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">many national parks are demarcated within nepal for trekking tourism, and there are among the locals some of the most hospitable hosts and indomitable guides in the world.  truly at present a mecca for anyone who wants to see giant mountains and accompanying culture.  tourist inflation is soaring, as globalisation adjusts prices to near western levels in tourist hotspots, in the 3rd poorest country in the world.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">But what you see here cannot help but change you.  Just everything is different.  And in a beautiful way, Nepal is so open to adventure - the feeling that with a pile of rupees in your hand &amp; a good pair of boots, you can go just about anywhere.  cheers to that.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Pakistan was a different case - the level of apprehension even at the name for americans now is steadily escalating, and the perception of that country has never been lower.  I am very lucky - I was able to visit in a period of stability during the summer of 2011 - i had put it off &amp; put it off, only to be able to take the plunge after a rought episode at work prompted a personal spell of recklessness - when i bought a plane ticket.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">best decision of my life - i loved every minute of pakistan, even when i was bitching:)  people there were so cool - present, not scamming you, open to real discussion, sad over the loss of friendship between our countries.  i met some wonderful guys &amp; pray we can turn it around.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In northern pakistan the himalayas end on the flanks of a mountain named nanga parbat.  another mountain range lies to the north of here, the karakoram range - with dimensions attaining similar magnitude in scale.  I was blessed to trek the baltoro glacier at least once, and photograph “the throne room of the mountain gods.”  The scale and architecture of these peaks is on another level - and the weather pattern in the karakoram is very different than the himalaya - with larger glaciers &amp; more instability.  for 15 days we drank water stained brown with the silty dust that rains off this similarly colored landscape.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">himalaya - \"abode of snow\" (sanskrit)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">karakoram - \"black rock\" (turkic)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">himal - \"mountain\" (sanskrit)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">chuli - \"mountain\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">tse - \"mountain\" (tibetan)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">la - \"high pass\" (tibetan)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ri - \"hill\" (tibetan)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">khola - \"river\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">sundar - \"handsome\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">kharka - \"shelter\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">machha - \"fish\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">puchare - \"tail\" (nepali)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brum - \"mountain\" (balti)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">gasher - \"beautiful\" (balti)</p>\r\n<b id=\"docs-internal-guid-612e253c-82c9-e896-89ff-aeca99288257\">masher - \"trigger\" (balti)</b>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2>A Section Title</h2>\r\n&nbsp;','<span class=\"small\">The</span><br />Location','','inherit','open','open','','88-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 18:23:20','2013-11-23 18:23:20','',88,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/88-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(253,1,'2013-11-23 18:23:48','2013-11-23 18:23:48','<p dir=\"ltr\">With the digital era photography has risen like a phoenix from it’s own ashes.  there is a level of control for the photographer (and especially the home photographer) previously unknown in the art.  From photoshop, photomerging, rgb printers, high sensitivity sensors, lens stabilization -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When my photography heroes came to the himalaya before me, they shot on film, and the earliest shot with tripods -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">vittorio sella came up the baltoro in 1909 with the duke of abruzzi and really introduced these mountains to the world - some of his photography here</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.panopticongallery.com/artist/vittorio_sella/#Vittorio_Sella_29.jpg\">http://www.panopticongallery.com/artist/vittorio_sella/#Vittorio_Sella_29.jpg</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">for american nature photographers ansel adams is the photographer to which all others seem a footnote - &amp; to his credit, his technique is very democratic, the zone system outlined in his masterpiece book “the negative” being the foundation upon which my photography is based.  as a man of his time, he shot with a large format camera &amp; a tripod, and of course the results speak for themselves</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ansel_Adams\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ansel_Adams</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">a photographer seminal to photographing just the himalayas is shiro shirahata.  his 2 folio books “nepal himalaya” &amp; “karakoram” begin to see the mountains themselves as characters - his books are portrait albums of the tallest mountains on earth.  his style represents the height of expedition style - on his treks he brought armies of porters, they hunted game, carried a large format camera &amp; a tripod.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html\">http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">galen rowell i see as an evolution to “alpine style”.  his tool of choice was the nikkor 20 mm f4 on a 35mm dslr - in other words, he could handhold the smaller, lighter, wide lensed camera, and get himself just about anywhere - a great climber in his own right with that camera.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html\">http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">just as the early siege expeditions to climb the great peaks have evolved to more lightweight attempts, we can see here that mountain photography has now paralleled that evolution through “alpine style” to what is now called “ultralight”.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">lens stabilization and the high sensitivities obtainable by digital sensors have made it possible now to shoot without a tripod - a seriously clunky encumbrance on uneven terrain in the mountains.  a cart full of giant photo plates has evolved to a backpack full of xray sensitive film cartridges and is now solid state media cards that you can slip in your pocket.  And everything has to get safely back from asia.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">shirahata - the culmination of expedition style</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">rowell - the dawn of alpine style and the nikkor 20 mm - evolution - but still carried film</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop.  rgb printers.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">the process - photoshopping &amp; photomerging - taking multiple photographs - high sensitivity sensors &amp; handheld - lens stabilizationthe images are merged - the advantage being that you can them make them pretty big as the combined effect makes for a massive image able</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photography “alpine style”</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">baryta paper - baryllium - testing - laboriously profiled</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">homemade - hand signed (image)</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">gear i have used that has made a difference</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon eos rebel t1i</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 15 - 85 mm is usm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 18 - 200 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nikkor 50 mm f1.2</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon 6d</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 24 -105 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 70 -200 mm t4</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brunton 26w solar charger</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">schneider polarizer</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop cs4 &amp; cs5</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ipf 6300 print plugin for photoshop</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">about sizing</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">i have unlimited editions of everything in their folio size -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">for larger blah blah limited editions</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">if you can dream it - i might be able to print it!  feel free to inquire about custom sizing over and above the x - large size!  some of them go even bigger...</p>','<span class=\"small\">The</span><br />Process','','inherit','open','open','','125-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 18:23:48','2013-11-23 18:23:48','',125,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/125-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(254,1,'2013-11-23 18:44:05','2013-11-23 18:44:05','<strong>makalu-barun national park, nepal</strong>\n\none of the benefits of trekking with a small crew is the logistical freedom to chase the light.  lanmale kharka had been described to me as \"the sound of music meets 7 years in tibet\" - praise indeed, coming from the modern alpinist don bowie.  i decided to try my hand at capturing this idea - &amp; with a short day from makalu basecamp to get down, and the afternoon to scout out the angles, i was ready early in the morning - hoping to find shape among the stone enclosures standing before the mountains of dawn.\n\nof course, as in many cases, when the dawn actually came - my instinct pulled strongly in another direction - GO UP. luckily having recently been above 6000 meters, i was fully acclimated and able to scamper up the hillside above camp - and the result is what you see.  cheers to my korean movie friends who made camping here interesting and satisfying - fun to talk shop about the biz with members of the vibrant korean film community.  also fun to look down from my perch and watch them scampering about below, desperately shooting the golden hour with their cameras.\n\n<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/infopage2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-247 alignright\" alt=\"infopage2\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/infopage2-301x200.jpg\" width=\"301\" height=\"200\" /></a>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_186\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"298\"]<img class=\"wp-image-186 \" alt=\"from_langmale_kharka_SAMPLE\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_langmale_kharka_SAMPLE-425x300.jpg\" width=\"298\" height=\"210\" /> Detail Sample<b> </b>[/caption]','dawn from langmale kharka','','inherit','open','open','','180-autosave-v1','','','2013-11-23 18:44:05','2013-11-23 18:44:05','',180,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/180-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(255,2,'2013-11-23 18:53:24','2013-11-23 18:53:24','[justified_image_grid preset=3 row_height=300 height_deviation=40 caption=fade min_height=600 orderby=menu_order last_row=flexible disable_cropping=yes developer_link=hide load_more=scroll load_more_limit=6 recent_posts=yes recents_post_type=product]','<span class=\"small\">Doug Kofsky</span><br />MOUNTAINSCAPES','','inherit','open','open','','38-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 18:53:24','2013-11-23 18:53:24','',38,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/38-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(256,2,'2013-11-23 18:56:14','2013-11-23 18:56:14','[justified_image_grid preset=3 row_height=300 height_deviation=40 caption=fade min_height=600 orderby=menu_order last_row=flexible disable_cropping=yes developer_link=hide load_more=scroll load_more_limit=6 recent_posts=yes recents_post_type=product]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n','<span class=\"small\">Doug Kofsky</span><br /><strong>M O U N T A I N S C A P E S</strong>','','inherit','open','open','','38-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 18:56:14','2013-11-23 18:56:14','',38,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/38-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(257,2,'2013-11-23 18:57:13','2013-11-23 18:57:13','[justified_image_grid preset=3 row_height=300 height_deviation=40 caption=fade min_height=600 orderby=menu_order last_row=flexible disable_cropping=yes developer_link=hide load_more=scroll load_more_limit=6 recent_posts=yes recents_post_type=product]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n','<span class=\"small\">Doug Kofsky</span><br /><strong>MOUNTAINSCAPES</strong','','inherit','open','open','','38-revision-v1','','','2013-11-23 18:57:13','2013-11-23 18:57:13','',38,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/38-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(258,2,'2013-12-07 21:06:22','2013-12-07 21:06:22','<strong>Shigar River Valley, Pakistan</strong>\n\nthe brown hues represented in this photo permeate the palette of color from from karakoram highway onwards.  the simplification of color distills the form of the mountains so beautifully here - and the tone is instilled in the sky by  the wind whipping the brown dust into air.  it settles into every nook and cranny of your gear, and stains the silty drinking water collected from the glacial melt.  the shigar charges by, rolling boulders along it\'s brown roiling depths, filling the air with noises that sound like a low coffee grinder.\n\nstill low down here, in a junction of glacial valleys, but the drama is in the air - the big mountains are close.\n\nmerge of 7 photographs – Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 18mm/f10.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/80th second exposure @ ISO 100.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_164\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"587\"]<img class=\" wp-image-164   \" alt=\"Detail View\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/sunset_from_korophon_sample.jpg\" width=\"587\" height=\"396\" /> detail[/caption]','sunset from korophon','','inherit','open','open','','162-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-07 21:06:22','2013-12-07 21:06:22','',162,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/162-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(259,2,'2013-11-23 20:43:29','2013-11-23 20:43:29','<strong>nepal himalaya</strong>\r\n\r\none of the \"money shots\" of the himalaya and an often photographed, often reproduced representation of the awesome power of the range.  i had set as my objective for this trek to photograph the giant rhododendron blossoms in front of the himalaya - this shot was a preconceived shot in my mind.  feeling the weight of these expectations, i decided to take a couple of days in the easy living village of ghorepani, lying at poon hill\'s base.  The village is a veritable beverly hills of tourist generated wealth in this curious country.  i had a wonderful time, with a revolving cast of fellow trekkers from every corner of the globe for company.\r\n\r\nall good - with the dense, growing cluster of hotels being attached to the hillside - the key to this area is the abundance of good water - a necessity for the accompanying comforts of the annapurna region.  a great success story for the local people &amp; a testament to their industry.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_262\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"351\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_poon_hill_sample-1.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-262 \" alt=\"detail\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_poon_hill_sample-1.jpg\" width=\"351\" height=\"238\" /></a> detail[/caption]','dhaulagiri I & rhododendrons from poon hill','','publish','open','closed','','dhaulagiri-rhododendrons-from-poon-hill','','','2013-11-23 21:05:42','2013-11-23 21:05:42','',0,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=259',47,'product','',0),(260,2,'2013-11-23 20:42:04','2013-11-23 20:42:04','','S_R_G_B_TEST','','inherit','open','open','','s_r_g_b_test','','','2013-11-23 20:42:04','2013-11-23 20:42:04','',259,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/S_R_G_B_TEST.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(261,2,'2013-11-23 21:04:44','2013-11-23 21:04:44','<strong>nepal himalaya</strong>\n\none of the \"money shots\" of the himalaya and an often photographed, often reproduced representation of the awesome power of the range.  i had set as my objective for this trek to photograph the giant rhododendron blossoms in front of the himalaya - this shot was a preconceived shot in my mind.  feeling the weight of these expectations, i decided to take a couple of days in the easy living village of ghorepani, lying at poon hill\'s b, a veritable beverly hills of tourist generated wealth in this curious country.  i had a wonderful time, with a revolving cast of fellow trekkers from every corner of the globe.\n\nall good - with the dense, growing cluster of hotels being attached to the hillside - the key to this area is the abundance of good water - a necessity for the accompanying comforts of the annapurna region.  a great success story for the local people &amp; testament to their industry.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_262\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"351\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_poon_hill_sample-1.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-262 \" alt=\"detail\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_poon_hill_sample-1.jpg\" width=\"351\" height=\"238\" /></a> detail[/caption]','dhaulagiri I & rhododendrons from poon hill','','inherit','open','open','','259-autosave-v1','','','2013-11-23 21:04:44','2013-11-23 21:04:44','',259,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/259-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(262,2,'2013-11-23 20:52:51','2013-11-23 20:52:51','','from_poon_hill_sample-1','detail','inherit','open','open','','from_poon_hill_sample-1','','','2013-11-23 20:52:51','2013-11-23 20:52:51','',259,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_poon_hill_sample-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(263,2,'2013-11-23 23:15:09','2013-11-23 23:15:09','<strong>From the Trek Around Manaslu - Nepal</strong>\r\n\r\nthis is from early on, around manaslu with purna and ramesh as a team for the first time.  we were quite low down, it was early in the trek, and i saw the river framed this way between the two steep hills, and i wanted to line things up just so with the vegetation.  it took a little wiggling around off the trail this way and that, til i found a small clearing where everything looked just right.  got the shot and then found them up ahead, confused and concerned a tiger might have gotten me.\r\n\r\nwater that drains off of the himalaya, north or south, must eventually flow south in order to obey gravity downward toward the indian ocean.  the rivers to the north of the range must cut their way through, and the result is the incredible relief in the gorges they make.  from here we are still quite low down, yet nearby lies terrain above 8000 meters.  this is so amazing about nepal - the relief of the south side and the scale of the vistas, as well as the accomodating climate of the relative lowlands. balmy sunny day wearing a t-shirt.  we eventually followed the river up and around the range to the north - of course quite a different story &amp; the end of t-shirt weather.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','budhi gandaki river','','publish','open','closed','','budhi-gandaki-river','','','2013-12-15 16:33:56','2013-12-15 16:33:56','',0,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=263',29,'product','',0),(264,2,'2013-11-23 23:13:58','2013-11-23 23:13:58','','budhi_gandaki_river','','inherit','open','open','','budhi_gandaki_river','','','2013-11-23 23:13:58','2013-11-23 23:13:58','',263,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/budhi_gandaki_river.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(265,2,'2013-11-23 23:23:10','2013-11-23 23:23:10','<strong>Langtang Himalaya, Nepal</strong>\r\n\r\npangsang lek was an unexplored area i had scouted via map and line of sight from my journey into the langtang valley.  it looked like a good place to get up above the trees for a look at the ganesh himalaya across the valley to the west, as well as perhaps a close inspection of the flanks of the langtang group.  after some adventures avoiding overzealous would be guides disguised as drunken sherpas i finally found an oasis at the hotel of kanji tamang sherpa, in the village of khanjim.\r\n\r\ni\'d set out in the dark to get here as usual, and the terrain was high kharka country, seasonal grazing for the animals, abandoned at this time of year, which was winter.  in my pocket i carried yak cheese i had bought and fresh bread baked below by my lovely hostess, rolling it with her hands at the edge of the fire while we smoked there and hung out the night before in the village.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_267\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"562\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_pangsang_lek_SAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-267  \" alt=\"from_pangsang_lek_SAMPLE\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_pangsang_lek_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"562\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','from pangsang lek','','publish','open','closed','','from-pangsang-lek','','','2013-12-15 19:27:34','2013-12-15 19:27:34','',0,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=265',33,'product','',0),(266,2,'2013-11-23 23:20:43','2013-11-23 23:20:43','','from_pangsang_lekMEDIUM','','inherit','open','open','','from_pangsang_lekmedium','','','2013-11-23 23:20:43','2013-11-23 23:20:43','',265,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_pangsang_lekMEDIUM.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(267,2,'2013-11-23 23:22:18','2013-11-23 23:22:18','','from_pangsang_lek_SAMPLE','','inherit','open','open','','from_pangsang_lek_sample','','','2013-11-23 23:22:18','2013-11-23 23:22:18','',265,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_pangsang_lek_SAMPLE.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(268,2,'2013-11-23 23:27:26','2013-11-23 23:27:26','<strong>From the Godwin-Austen Glacier - Karakoram Range, Pakistan</strong>\r\n\r\nwanted the biggest shot i could get of the biggest baddest mountain of them all - k2.  huffing along on the way to broad peak base camp i had the shot over &amp; over again - so decided to experiment with shooting the south face in sections and merging the pieces in photoshop.\r\n\r\nthe result is what you see - 22 images merged together - an attempt to look closely at the terrain comprising in my opinion the most significant historical mountain face on earth.\r\n\r\nfrom this vantage many significant routes up the mountain are visible - the abruzzi ridge, the south face route, the west ridge, the magic line.\r\n\r\nthis photo is dedicated to tadeusz piotrowski and wojciech wroz - polish pioneers on 2 of these unbelievable routes of inspiration - who were lost on the way back to earth.\r\n\r\nmerge of 22 photographs - Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 85mm/f20.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/80th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_270\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"577\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/k2_8611m_sample.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-270 \" alt=\"k2_8611m_sample\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/k2_8611m_sample.jpg\" width=\"577\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','k2 (8611m)','','publish','open','closed','','k2-8611m','','','2013-12-03 15:00:50','2013-12-03 15:00:50','',0,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=268',11,'product','',0),(269,2,'2013-11-23 23:25:43','2013-11-23 23:25:43','','k2_8611m','','inherit','open','open','','k2_8611m','','','201