nalways lovin the sight of lenpo gang - it gives the impression of something amazing on the horizon &amp; is one of the far away big boys flanking langtang lirung - &amp; of course Tibet so close - if only one could just walk over - in order to say \"i have been to Tibet\".\n\nsome day...\n\nmerge of 11 photographs - Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 16mm/f16.  EOS Rebel T1i 1/60th second exposure @ 100 ISO.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_154\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"584\"]<img class=\" wp-image-154  \" alt=\"Detail View\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/tree_shadow_on_phusang_danda_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"584\" height=\"396\" /> detail[/caption]','tree shadow on phusang danda','','inherit','open','open','','152-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-01 19:07:53','2013-12-01 19:07:53','',152,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/152-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(401,2,'2013-12-04 00:52:44','2013-12-04 00:52:44','<strong>Karakoram range, Pakistan</strong>\n\nwe are given a couple of rare opportunities this time around and i was lucky enough to be inspired &amp; ready to seize one of them.\n\nmy hope and goal as a photographer is that i haven\'t left much to say.\n\nthis is nameless tower.  people want to come from all over the place to climb it.  i totally get that.\n\nCanon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 85mm/f11.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/125th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.','nameless tower (6239m)','','inherit','open','open','','374-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-04 00:52:44','2013-12-04 00:52:44','',374,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/374-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(402,2,'2013-12-02 01:19:41','2013-12-02 01:19:41','<strong>Night falling on the Manaslu Himalaya</strong>\n\nafter trekking around manaslu i wanted to take the trek to the next level by finding a new vantage point from which to photograph her &amp; her neighbors - so purna, ramesh &amp; i hunted around and tried to get up the hill above syange village in order to photograph the massif from across the marsyangdi valley.\n\nit took some doing - hacking through jungle &amp; a few detours - but we found the right ridge and most importantly we found water above the trees.  thusly we were able to make a go of a day of going as high as we could up into the foothills of the lamjung himalaya during our 7 day mini-expedition.\n\nthe climb of sundar ri culminated in this sunset on our descent.  the southwest faces of phungi himal, manaslu, ngadi chuli, himal chuli, and boudha himal float above the clouds arriving from india, crashing into the range, and funneling up the marsyangdi.  3 of the 48 tallest mountains on earth in this crown one circumnavigates to complete the trek around manaslu.\n\nmerge of 11 photographs - Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 15mm/f10.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/80th second exposure @ ISO 100.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_377\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"522\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/sunset_from_sundar_sample1.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-377 \" alt=\"sunset_from_sundar_sample\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/sunset_from_sundar_sample1.jpg\" width=\"522\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','sunset from sundar','','inherit','open','open','','376-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-02 01:19:41','2013-12-02 01:19:41','',376,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/376-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(403,2,'2013-12-01 20:01:17','2013-12-01 20:01:17','','sunrise_from_tashigaun_sample','','inherit','open','open','','sunrise_from_tashigaun_sample-2','','','2013-12-01 20:01:17','2013-12-01 20:01:17','',165,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/sunrise_from_tashigaun_sample1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(404,2,'2013-12-04 01:02:51','2013-12-04 01:02:51','<strong>Annapurna Himalaya, Nepal</strong>\n\nanother obsessive quest for a fresh vista led me to namchung ri, an obscure hill in the central annapurna foothills.  the approach starts from pokhara via via taxi or the dreaded bus so i usually opt for the former.  then 1/2 a day hike up my secret valley &amp; through the maze up the flanks of namchung, whose top reveals the iconic machhapuchare, translated as \"fishtail\" in nepali bhasa.\n\ni made 2 attempts at the top and made it both times - the first time in a howling storm that obscured everything and soaked me through - this after a night huddling in a cave during a lightning storm, trying to master the intricacies of kindling bamboo &amp; wet wood.  epic failure in terms of getting a fire lit or getting my shot, but successful in that at least i knew how to get here again, and how to negotiate the labrynth of buffalo trails running up and down the hillside.\n\n1 month later i was back, and i carrying a tent to boot - a rarity for me in the hospitable himalayas.  managed to shake out early and grab this one in a rare moment of good weather during the early monsoon.\n\nmerge of 13 photographs - Canon EF 24 -105 mm @ 105mm/f13.  Canon EOS 6D 1/200th second exposure @ ISO 400.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe DNG Converter/Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n<div></div>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_368\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"577\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/machhapuchare_and_surrounding_peaks_from_namchung_ri_SAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-368 \" alt=\"machhapuchare_and_surrounding_peaks_from_namchung_ri_SAMPLE\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/machhapuchare_and_surrounding_peaks_from_namchung_ri_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"577\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','macchapuchare (6997m) from namchung ri','','inherit','open','open','','366-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-04 01:02:51','2013-12-04 01:02:51','',366,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/366-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(406,2,'2013-12-02 01:56:16','2013-12-02 01:56:16','<strong>From the Baltoro Glacier - Karakoram Range, Pakistan</strong>\n\ntook this one with young kai - a strapping english lad whose youthful energy i was drawn to and whose company suited me great while we shared a tent on the k2 trek.  we were wandering around gore camp after dinner during the perfect lengthening of a summer day in valhalla.\n\nto think of the paths we take and all of mine that had led me here to this dream - 10 years to get here it seemed &amp; this brilliant kid was coming here in his early 20\'s.\n\ni remember my early 20\'s and how it was the beginning of your professional path - if i had come here then as opposed to 20 years later would my path have turned differently?\n\nmerge of 5 photographs - Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 35mm/f25.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/60th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n&nbsp;','masherbrum & penitentes II','','inherit','open','open','','316-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-02 01:56:16','2013-12-02 01:56:16','',316,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/316-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(407,2,'2013-12-02 02:14:39','2013-12-02 02:14:39','<strong>From the climb of Tsergo Ri - Langtang Himalaya, Nepal</strong>\n\nprolonged exposure to trekking had taken my body to the point where my stomach was now a bottomless well which no amount of rice &amp; lentisl could be up to the task to fill.  i was summarily asked to leave one guesthouse after dinner one night by the local sisters who witnessed the carnage at the dinner table - they had 50 koreans &amp; accompanying support coming in on a 3 day so i was clearly expendable to their immediate plans.\n\nfeeling unwanted, i wandered out of the village at 2 a.m in order to attempt a night ascent of tsergo ri - a mound of rock from whose top one gets perspective on the west face of langtang lirung &amp; langtang II catching the first rays of sun from the east.  so peaceful to be trekking in the night, with the infinite stillness of these mountains as your intimate companion.  and the arrival of the day is the revelation of color.\n\nmerge of 2 photographs - Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 31mm/f11.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/80th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe  CPhotoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n<div></div>','dawn on langtang lirung (7227m)','','inherit','open','open','','314-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-02 02:14:39','2013-12-02 02:14:39','',314,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/314-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(408,2,'2013-12-02 14:34:03','2013-12-02 14:34:03','<strong>Karakoram Range, Pakistan</strong>\n\na recurring phenomenon i experience with himalayan photography is that the very special shots arrive in bunches, usually around some fleeting magical moment in the mountains. the sunrise of august 15 was one of those moments. in 20 seconds i recorded 3 photographs of the sun kissing nameless tower and uli biaho as the swirling mist prepared to close in again. and just like that, it was gone. i have to admit, it was great to come back down to camp with everyone just waking up to cloudy skies. the effect was like a champagne cork - finally i could relax, i\'d gotten something i\'d come for.\n\nCanon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 85mm/f11.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/125th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.','uli biaho (6109m)','','inherit','open','open','','355-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-02 14:34:03','2013-12-02 14:34:03','',355,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/355-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(409,2,'2013-12-02 15:10:18','2013-12-02 15:10:18','<strong>Langtang Himalaya, Nepal - Ganesh Himalaya &amp; Tibet on the Horizon</strong>\n\ni found phusang danda after an aborted bus ride - some cross country adjustments across helambu and here we were - perfect.  a salute to the spirit of nepal &amp; the ability for the independent trekker there to change the plan.\n\nwalked in here @ 11 in the morning &amp; something just screamed out in me - \"STAY HERE\".  spent the day sipping tea with a local kid @ his little teahouse &amp; wandering around on a sort of mini scout.   the evening brought this little vista when everything in the sky started banging away.\n\nmerge of 11 photographs - Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 20mm/f16.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/80th second exposure @ ISO 400.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe DNG Converter/Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_138\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"558\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_phusang_danda_sample.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-138\" alt=\"from_phusang_danda_sample\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_phusang_danda_sample.jpg\" width=\"558\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','from phusang danda','','inherit','open','open','','136-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-02 15:10:18','2013-12-02 15:10:18','',136,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/136-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(410,2,'2013-12-03 14:52:45','2013-12-03 14:52:45','<strong>From the Godwin-Austen Glacier - Karakoram Range, Pakistan</strong>\n\nwanted the biggest shot i could get of the biggest baddest mountain of them all - k2.  huffing along on the way to broad peak base camp i had the shot over &amp; over again - so decided to experiment with shooting the south face in sections and merging the pieces in photoshop.\n\nthe result is what you see - 22 images merged together - an attempt to look closely at the terrain comprising in my opinion the most significant historical mountain face on earth.\n\nfrom this vantage many significant routes up the mountain are visible - the abruzzi ridge, the south face route, the west ridge, the magic line.\n\nthis photo is dedicated to tadeusz piotrowski and wojciech wroz - polish pioneers on 2 of these unbelievable routes of inspiration - who were lost on the way back to earth.\n\nmerge of 22 photographs - Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 85mm/f20.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/80th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_270\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"577\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/k2_8611m_sample.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-270 \" alt=\"k2_8611m_sample\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/k2_8611m_sample.jpg\" width=\"577\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','k2 (8611m)','','inherit','open','open','','268-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-03 14:52:45','2013-12-03 14:52:45','',268,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/268-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(411,2,'2013-12-02 16:16:09','2013-12-02 16:16:09','[justified_image_grid preset=4 row_height=300 height_deviation=40 caption=fade min_height=600 orderby=menu_order last_row=flexible disable_cropping=yes developer_link=hide load_more=scroll load_more_limit=6 recent_posts=yes recents_post_type=product]','<strong>M O U N T A I N S C A P E S</strong>','','inherit','open','open','','38-revision-v1','','','2013-12-02 16:16:09','2013-12-02 16:16:09','',38,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/38-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(412,2,'2013-12-02 16:20:12','2013-12-02 16:20:12','[justified_image_grid preset=4 row_height=500 height_deviation=40 caption=fade min_height=600 orderby=menu_order last_row=flexible disable_cropping=yes developer_link=hide load_more=scroll load_more_limit=6 recent_posts=yes recents_post_type=product]','<strong>M O U N T A I N S C A P E S</strong>','','inherit','open','open','','38-revision-v1','','','2013-12-02 16:20:12','2013-12-02 16:20:12','',38,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/38-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(414,2,'2013-12-02 16:46:09','2013-12-02 16:46:09','<p dir=\"ltr\">With the digital era photography has risen like a phoenix from it’s own ashes.  there is a level of control for the photographer (and especially the home photographer) previously unknown in the art.  From photoshop, photomerging, rgb printers, high sensitivity sensors, lens stabilization -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When my photography heroes came to the himalaya before me, they shot on film, and the earliest shot with tripods -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">vittorio sella came up the baltoro in 1909 with the duke of abruzzi and really introduced these mountains to the world - some of his photography here</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b><a title=\"vittorio sella\" href=\"http://www.panopticongallery.com/artist/vittorio_sella/#Vittorio_Sella_29.jpg\">Vittorio Sella</a>\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>for american nature photographers ansel adams is the photographer to which all others seem a footnote - &amp; to his credit, his technique is very democratic, the zone system outlined in his masterpiece book “the negative” being the foundation upon which my photography is based.  as a man of his time, he shot with a large format camera &amp; a tripod, and of course the results speak for themselves\r\n\r\n<a title=\"ansel adams\" href=\"http://en.wikipediAnsel Adams\">Ansel Adams</a>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">a photographer seminal to photographing just the himalayas is shiro shirahata.  his 2 folio books “nepal himalaya” &amp; “karakoram” begin to see the mountains themselves as characters - his books are portrait albums of the tallest mountains on earth.  his style represents the height of expedition style - on his treks he brought armies of porters, they hunted game, carried a large format camera &amp; a tripod.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html\">http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">galen rowell i see as an evolution to “alpine style”.  his tool of choice was the nikkor 20 mm f4 on a 35mm dslr - in other words, he could handhold the smaller, lighter, wide lensed camera, and get himself just about anywhere - a great climber in his own right with that camera.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html\">http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html</a></p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">just as the early siege expeditions to climb the great peaks have evolved to more lightweight attempts, we can see here that mountain photography has now paralleled that evolution through “alpine style” to what is now called “ultralight”.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">lens stabilization and the high sensitivities obtainable by digital sensors have made it possible now to shoot without a tripod - a seriously clunky encumbrance on uneven terrain in the mountains.  a cart full of giant photo plates has evolved to a backpack full of xray sensitive film cartridges and is now solid state media cards that you can slip in your pocket.  And everything has to get safely back from asia.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">shirahata - the culmination of expedition style</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">rowell - the dawn of alpine style and the nikkor 20 mm - evolution - but still carried film</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop.  rgb printers.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">the process - photoshopping &amp; photomerging - taking multiple photographs - high sensitivity sensors &amp; handheld - lens stabilizationthe images are merged - the advantage being that you can them make them pretty big as the combined effect makes for a massive image able</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photography “alpine style”</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">baryta paper - baryllium - testing - laboriously profiled</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">homemade - hand signed (image)</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">gear i have used that has made a difference</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon eos rebel t1i</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 15 - 85 mm is usm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 18 - 200 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nikkor 50 mm f1.2</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon 6d</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 24 -105 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 70 -200 mm t4</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brunton 26w solar charger</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">schneider polarizer</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop cs4 &amp; cs5</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ipf 6300 print plugin for photoshop</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">about sizing</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">i have unlimited editions of everything in their folio size -</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">for larger blah blah limited editions</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">if you can dream it - i might be able to print it!  feel free to inquire about custom sizing over and above the x - large size!  some of them go even bigger...</p>','The Process','','inherit','open','open','','125-revision-v1','','','2013-12-02 16:46:09','2013-12-02 16:46:09','',125,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/125-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(415,2,'2013-12-02 17:31:09','2013-12-02 17:31:09','','Variation #415 of sunset from sundar','','publish','open','open','','product-376-variation','','','2013-12-02 17:31:09','2013-12-02 17:31:09','',376,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?product_variation=product-376-variation',0,'product_variation','',0),(416,2,'2013-12-02 17:31:09','2013-12-02 17:31:09','','Variation #416 of sunset from sundar','','publish','open','open','','product-376-variation-2','','','2013-12-02 17:31:09','2013-12-02 17:31:09','',376,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?product_variation=product-376-variation-2',1,'product_variation','',0),(423,1,'2013-12-02 19:51:50','2013-12-02 19:51:50','','Variation #423 of morning light on masherbrum (7821m)','','publish','open','open','','product-372-variation