- f64 meaning the smallest of aperture size and thus unlimited depth of field and great sharpness and clarity to the image.  the results speak for themselves:\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"shiro shirahata\" href=\"http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html\" target=\"_blank\">Shiro Shirahata</a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">a photographer seminal to photographing just the himalayas is shiro shirahata.  his 2 folio books “nepal himalaya” &amp; “karakoram” begin to see the mountains themselves as characters - his books are portrait albums of the tallest mountains on earth.  his style represents the height of expedition style - on his treks he brought armies of porters, they hunted game, carried a Hasselblad medium format &amp; tripod.   shirahata - the culmination of expedition style</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b><a title=\"galen rowell\" href=\" http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html \" target=\"_blank\">Galen Rowell</a>\r\n\r\ngalen rowell i see as an evolution to “alpine style”.  his tool of choice was the nikkor 20 mm f4 on a 35mm dslr - in other words, he could handhold the smaller, lighter, wide lensed camera, and get himself just about anywhere - a great climber in his own right with that camera.  rowell - the dawn of alpine style and the nikkor 20 mm - evolution - but still carried film  JUST AS ROWELLS TIME SAW ALPINE STYLE NOW IS\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>just as the early siege expeditions to climb the great peaks have evolved to more lightweight attempts, we can see here that mountain photography has now paralleled that evolution through “alpine style” to what is now called “ultralight”.\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">With the digital era photography has risen like a phoenix from it’s own ashes.  there is a level of control for the photographer (and especially the home photographer) previously unknown in the art.  From photoshop, photomerging, rgb printers, high sensitivity sensors, lens stabilization -</p>\r\n\r\n<div> lens stabilization and the high sensitivities obtainable by digital sensors have made it possible now to shoot without a tripod - a seriously clunky encumbrance on uneven terrain in the mountains.  a cart full of giant photo plates has evolved to a backpack full of xray sensitive film cartridges and is now solid state media cards that you can slip in your pocket.  And everything has to get safely back from asia.</div>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>photoshopping &amp; photomerging - taking multiple photographs - high sensitivity sensors &amp; handheld - lens stabilizationthe images are merged - the advantage being that you can them make them pretty big as the combined effect makes for a massive image able\r\n\r\nphotoshop.  rgb printers.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photography “alpine style”</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">baryta paper - baryllium - testing - laboriously profiled</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">homemade - hand signed (image)</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">gear i have used that has made a difference</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon eos rebel t1i</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 15 - 85 mm is usm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 18 - 200 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nikkor 50 mm f1.2</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon 6d</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 24 -105 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 70 -200 mm t4</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brunton 26w solar charger</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">schneider polarizer</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop cs4 &amp; cs5</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ipf 6300 print plugin for photoshop</p>\r\n about sizing\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>i have unlimited editions of everything in their folio size -\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>for larger blah blah limited editions\r\n\r\nif you can dream it - i might be able to print it!  feel free to inquire about custom sizing over and above the x - large size!  some of them go even bigger...','The Process','','inherit','open','open','','125-revision-v1','','','2013-12-04 00:15:32','2013-12-04 00:15:32','',125,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/125-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(445,2,'2013-12-04 01:22:52','2013-12-04 01:22:52','<strong>Manaslu Himalaya, Nepal - <strong>Ganesh Himalaya on the horizon</strong></strong>\n\na real turning point for me and learned something this day about my stubbornness.<strong><strong>\n</strong></strong>\n\nwanted to see manaslu across the way from the village of sama.  we were trying to make a real day of it so purna and i set out early &amp; ramesh baked tibetan bread in sama village behind us and then climbed up to us for lunch at a small col, with the kutang massif to our east and and sama ri just above to the west.\n\nthe northeastern slope appeared gradual enough, and a traversing ascent led eventually, quite close to the top, across a steep field of snow.  by now the route had crossed over so that the precipitous northwest face of sama dropped thousands of feet to the valley below, about 10 feet to the right.\n\npurna did not want to see me take the risk of crossing, and injury to me could ruin his professional reputation as well as put him &amp; ramesh needlessly at risk.  but i had summit fever &amp; this was terrain of a degree i\'d negotiated countless times when unguided.\n\nso i told them, wait for me there, and  i went anyway.  and i crossed some exposed terrain after that and topped out.  and i could see the ganesh himalaya, far on the horizon, glowing in perfection in the late afternoon sun, finally unobstructed at the very top.\n\nthe boys came up, and weren\'t annoyed, and we enjoyed this magic.  then we found a safer route back down and i\'d had my first really life changing day of the trip.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','the view from sama hill','','inherit','open','open','','348-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-04 01:22:52','2013-12-04 01:22:52','',348,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/348-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(446,2,'2013-12-04 01:48:28','2013-12-04 01:48:28','<strong>From Concordia - Karakoram Range, Pakistan</strong>\n\ni\'d had a rough day of it with my attempt to reach k2 basecamp derailed by explosive dysentery.  before crawling back into the tent i willed myself to wash my fouled gear and lay it out in the sun - then i passed out.\n\nwoke up in the evening &amp; indeed the weather signs were improving - and at last here was my first exposure to \"the shining wall\" - sunset on the absolutely one of a kind west face of gasherbrum IV.\n\ngasherbrum translates from balti as \"beautiful mountain\".  unbelievable as it is to fathom, this face has been climbed.  in 1985 wojciech kurtyka &amp; robert schauer climbed the complete face alpine style but had to abandon the summit in the face of exhaustion and bad weather.  still ranks in my book as one of the great achievements in the himalayas.\n\nCanon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 85mm/f11.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/125th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','sunset on gahserbrum IV with clouds','','inherit','open','open','','344-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-04 01:48:28','2013-12-04 01:48:28','',344,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/344-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(447,2,'2013-12-05 15:14:42','2013-12-05 15:14:42','<strong>From Japanese Camp</strong>\n\nwe spent a few days shuffling around on rocks stacked like dinner plates in order to visit makalu advanced camp - which lies 1000m above makalu basecamp and serves as the actual base for expeditions attempting to summit by the standard route.  it is tucked away up a tributary glacier of the barun at an altitiude of about 5700m, and every year an international city of tents grows here during expedition season.  i wanted to pay a visit to check out the scene &amp; speak some english.\n\nwe brought a snowstorm up with us, so everyone was hiding in their tent, but the sherpas invited us into one of the cook tents, and we swapped a few stories, drank some tea, and saw some state of the art high altitude cookware.  then i knocked on a few tent flaps &amp; met some pretty cool climbers.  that afternoon we returned in the elements to our tents here @ japanesese camp, an intermeditate stopping point along the glacier about 2/3 of the way up.\n\nthe evening broke up the storm and i was able to wander out into the vast expanse of rocks, freshly painted with the new fallen snow.  i loved the way the new snow filled in shadows beneath makalu, watching over us, fighting off the last clouds stubbornly clinging to her in the light of the setting sun.\n\nmerge of 4 photographs – Canon EF 24 -105 mm @ 35mm/f22.  Canon EOS 6D 1/80th second exposure @ ISO 320.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe DNG Converter/Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_336\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"585\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/makalu_sunset_from_japanese_camp_SAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-336 \" alt=\"makalu_sunset_from_japanese_camp_SAMPLE\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/makalu_sunset_from_japanese_camp_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"585\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','sunset on makalu (8481m)','','inherit','open','open','','334-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-05 15:14:42','2013-12-05 15:14:42','',334,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/334-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(448,2,'2013-12-05 15:10:03','2013-12-05 15:10:03','','Variation #448 of sunset on makalu (8481m)','','publish','open','open','','product-334-variation','','','2013-12-05 15:10:03','2013-12-05 15:10:03','',334,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?product_variation=product-334-variation',0,'product_variation','',0),(449,2,'2013-12-05 15:10:27','2013-12-05 15:10:27','','Variation #449 of sunset on makalu (8481m)','','publish','open','open','','product-334-variation-2','','','2013-12-05 15:10:27','2013-12-05 15:10:27','',334,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/?product_variation=product-334-variation-2',1,'product_variation','',0),(450,2,'2013-12-05 15:10:48','2