ug into the side of the valley, at the top of a slope under the massive flanks of the peak whose name it bears.  in order to attain a cleaner perspective on the trango &amp; cathedral group i decided to hike down to the river as close to the middle of the valley as possible.\n\nthat was entry point to the other world - the giants looming on the horizon, the clouds boiling and reforming, the small plants carving into the bed of the grinding, silty brown shigar.  i was mesmerized by the interplay of light and shadow on these iconic walls, above the snout of the mighty baltoro glacier, just ahead.\n\nmerge of 8 photographs – Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 50mm/f18.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/40th second exposure @ ISO 100.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_147\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"550\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/product/welcome-to-the-baltoro/welcome_to_the_baltoro_sample/#main\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-147\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-147\" alt=\"welcome_to_the_baltoro_sample\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/welcome_to_the_baltoro_sample.jpg\" width=\"550\" height=\"396\" /></a> Detail View[/caption]','welcome to the baltoro','','inherit','open','open','','145-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-05 18:18:55','2013-12-05 18:18:55','',145,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/145-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(455,2,'2013-12-05 18:31:19','2013-12-05 18:31:19','<strong>From Liligo Camp - Baltoro Glacier, Pakistan</strong>\n\nlast light on the lower baltoro &amp; not a cloud in the sky in liligo.  my trek mate ian had an 18 - 200 mm along so i borrowed it and went out to shoot cathedral spire.\n\nsingular in the power of its geometry, the cleanest shape in the whole valley, perfectly positioned to glow in the last light of day - cathedral spire is a shape that has inhabited the dreams of many a climber - an unadulterated idea of mountain form.\n\ncanon efs 18-200 @ 135mm f16 eos rebel t1i 1/400sec 200iso raw photoshop cs5 mac','cathedral spire (5866m)','','inherit','open','open','','291-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-05 18:31:19','2013-12-05 18:31:19','',291,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/291-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(456,2,'2013-12-07 20:35:44','2013-12-07 20:35:44','<strong>Annapurna Himalaya, Nepal</strong>\n\nthe recently opened mardi himal basecamp trek ascends a long ridge through rhododendron jungle and then above onto the flanks of the annapurna himalaya, under the shadow of the incomparable machhapuchare, or \"fishtail\".\n\nthis vista is called \"1st viewpoint\" and is the initial point at which you pop out of the trees enough to really see where you are.  it also showcases a very rare stand of pristine himalayan rhododendron, which i had taken as my primary photographic objective for the trek.  after passing here 2 times in tantalizingly close but not quite suitable photographic conditions my stubbornness would not let me leave without getting this shot.  i resolved to retrace my steps here after a nights rest below at the machhapuchare guesthouse, operated by the brothers bhim &amp; khim tamang.\n\ni really shared some fine times with those brothers - so alike looking but so different from one another - bhim scrupulous and polite to a fault, his english carefully crafted from 6 years of clerical work in saudi arabia.  he taught myself and my friends some superb card games, which became a staple of the trek from then on.  khim, the elder brother, shifty, opportunistic, but able to go with the plan - like when he told me where the local ganja grew or when i told him i would be getting up @ 3 am to go back up and get the shot.  and the 3rd time was a charm.\n\nmerge of 28 photographs – Canon EF 24 -105 mm @ 32mm/f22.  Canon EOS 6D 1/50th second exposure @ ISO 400.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe DNG Converter/Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_303\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"584\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_the_mardi_himalSAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-303 \" alt=\"from_the_mardi_himalSAMPLE\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_the_mardi_himalSAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"584\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','from the mardi himal','','inherit','open','open','','301-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-07 20:35:44','2013-12-07 20:35:44','',301,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/301-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(457,2,'2013-12-07 21:16:20','2013-12-07 21:16:20','<strong>Sunrise from Ranipauwa - Rasuwa District, Nepal</strong>\n<p id=\"yui_3_11_0_3_1386450473510_1558\">a \"chakkajam\" - road strike - had stopped any chance of catching a bus from kathmandu to langtang for at least 2 days.</p>\nas my mates cracked their beers and resigned themselves to more waiting, i had the realization that i could not endure that smoggy hellhole another minute.  i decided i would walk to langtang - the way trekkers used to 30 years ago - right down that same road that any other day in this era would be chaotically choked with buses, cars and other implements of pedestrian death.\n<p id=\"yui_3_11_0_3_1386450473510_1564\">walking that road, leaving the city behind, stopping for noodles, meeting people, the villagers were drying their crops on tarpaulins laid out on the asphalt.  and quiet as a church. i managed to walk in one day what can be driven in 2 hours. there was one hotel in ranipauwa, where i stayed with some nice kids, and when i awoke the following morning and stepped out to look around, there it was.</p>\nCanon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 35mm/f9.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/160th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.','ganesh & and helambu dawn','','inherit','open','open','','330-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-07 21:16:20','2013-12-07 21:16:20','',330,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/330-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(458,2,'2013-12-07 21:44:38','2013-12-07 21:44:38','<strong>From the Trek Around Manaslu, Nepal</strong>\n\none of our earliest adventures off the beaten track, with my local guys purna &amp; ramesh, to this vista from above the village of sama.  we were able to bushwhack up the hill behind the village to a ridge that crested treeline and gave views across to the kutang himalaya basking in the setting sun.  ramesh was 18 years old then &amp; in his element, oftentimes using branches &amp; vines to support hurtling himself through the steep terrain.\n\nin my eagerness i had pressed to accomplish this foray up the hill soon after our arrival in sama, but i had not yet learned the lesson that for me trekking north of the himalaya in winter is more difficult than trekking south of the range - we frequently had a giant mountain between us and the sun, and the solar warmth of the southern aspects makes all the difference for me. being cold &amp; in the shade had added quite a few meters as to how i was feeling in regards the altitude, but you can\'t let that stand in your way sometimes - who knows when you will ever come back?\n\nso i remember suffering a little for this one &amp; afterwards retreating back down to a lower village in order to clear a raging migraine.  but from this point i could clearly make out a saddle that promised a possible future attempt on sama ri, which was a major coup for us i thought.  and we were able to go to a new vantage point to take some mountainscapes, and not for the last time.  cheers to that.\n\nmerge of 8 photographs – Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 15mm/f11.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/250th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n<div></div>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_329\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"586\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/kutang_himalaya_from_above_sama_SAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-329  \" alt=\"detail\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/kutang_himalaya_from_above_sama_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"586\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','kutang himalaya from above sama','','inherit','open','open','','327-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-07 21:44:38','2013-12-07 21:44:38','',327,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/327-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(459,2,'2013-12-07 21:59:28','2013-12-07 21:59:28','<strong>Karakoram Range, Pakistan</strong>\n\none of the crueler fates assigned to a creature would be the toil of a pack horse on the baltoro - the terrain is nothing if not leg breaking &amp; many of their sad &amp; desiccated carcasses litter the glacier and put the blot of man on gods immaculate work.  a barbaric practice that unfortunately still economically justifies itself as horses do not go on strike or change the deal and a horse can carry more without complaint and yet his life is worth less.\n\nthis i feel compelled to mention even as i have exploited these animals myself to provide perspective for the awesome dimensions of the karakoram.  i pray for their salvation and hope that perhaps the decline of tourism in pakistan, so tragic to me on a deeply personal level, will reduce the use of pack horses to carry supplies on the baltoro.\n\nmerge of 3 photographs – Canon EF-S 15 -85 mm @ 15mm/f11.  Canon EOS Rebel T1i 1/250th second exposure @ ISO 200.  Camera Raw processed &amp; profiled with Adobe Photoshop CS5/Canon IPF 16 bit print plug-in for Photoshop.\n<div></div>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_326\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"574\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/horses_on_the_baltoro_SAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-326  \" alt=\"detail\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/horses_on_the_baltoro_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"574\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','horses on the baltoro','','inherit','open','open','','324-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-07 21:59:28','2013-12-07 21:59:28','',324,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/324-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(460,2,'2013-12-08 00:09:48','2013-12-08 00:09:48','<p dir=\"ltr\"> in my photography i use for inspiration the standards set forth by my photography heroes who came to the himalaya before me.  Of course they shot on film, and the earliest shot with tripods -</p>\r\n <a title=\"vittorio sella\" href=\"http://www.panopticongallery.com/artist/vittorio_sella/#Vittorio_Sella_29.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">Vittorio Sella</a>\r\n\r\nVittorio Sella came up the baltoro in 1909 with the duke of abruzzi and really introduced these mountains to the world - and he shot on 30 x 40 cm glass plates!  The abbruzzi expedition photos are magnificent and have touched the heart of many a mountaineer.  some of his photography here:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"ansel adams\" href=\"http://en.wikipediAnsel Adams\" target=\"_blank\">Ansel Adams</a>\r\n\r\nFor american nature photographers ansel adams is the photographer to which all others seem a footnote - &amp; to his credit, his technique is very democratic, the zone system outlined in his masterpiece book “the negative” being the foundation upon which my photography is based.  as a man of his time, he shot with a large format camera &amp; a tripod at f64 - f64 meaning the smallest of aperture size and thus unlimited depth of field and great sharpness and clarity to the image.  capturing detail in the nooks and crannies of ice and rock is the essence of mountain photography.  i was inspired by the way that ansel adams worked with the texture of granite cliffs, desert badlands, or adobe,the results speak for themselves:\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"shiro shirahata\" href=\"http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html\" target=\"_blank\">Shiro Shirahata</a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">a photographer seminal to photographing just the himalayas is shiro shirahata.  his 2 folio books “nepal himalaya” &amp; “karakoram” begin to see the mountains themselves as characters - his books are portrait albums of the tallest mountains on earth.  his style represents the height of expedition style - on his treks he brought armies of porters, they hunted game, carried a Hasselblad medium format &amp; tripod.   shirahata - the culmination of expedition style</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b><a title=\"galen rowell\" href=\" http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html \" target=\"_blank\">Galen Rowell</a>\r\n\r\ngalen rowell i see as an evolution to “alpine style”.  his tool of choice was the nikkor 20 mm f4 on a 35mm dslr - in other words, he could handhold the smaller, lighter, wide lensed camera, and get himself just about anywhere - a great climber in his own right with that camera.  rowell - the dawn of alpine style and the nikkor 20 mm - evolution - but still carried film  JUST AS ROWELLS TIME SAW ALPINE STYLE NOW IS\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>just as the early siege expeditions to climb the great peaks have evolved to more lightweight attempts, we can see here that mountain photography has now paralleled that evolution through “alpine style” to what is now called “ultralight”.\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">With the digital era photography has risen like a phoenix from it’s own ashes.  there is a level of control for the photographer (and especially the home photographer) previously unknown in the art.  From photoshop, photomerging, rgb printers, high sensitivity sensors, lens stabilization -</p>\r\n\r\n<div> lens stabilization and the high sensitivities obtainable by digital sensors have made it possible now to shoot without a tripod - a seriously clunky encumbrance on uneven terrain in the mountains.  a cart full of giant photo plates has evolved to a backpack full of xray sensitive film cartridges and is now solid state media cards that you can slip in your pocket.  And everything has to get safely back from asia.</div>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>photoshopping &amp; photomerging - taking multiple photographs - high sensitivity sensors &amp; handheld - lens stabilizationthe images are merged - the advantage being that you can them make them pretty big as the combined effect makes for a massive image possible.  merge of photographs - the photographer now has the ability to shoot overlapping sections of a scene and merge the pieces in photoshop - my giant panoramas are all explorations of this ability.\r\n\r\nphotoshop.  rgb printers.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photography “alpine style”</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">baryta paper - baryllium - testing - laboriously profiled</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">homemade - hand signed (image)</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">gear i have used that has made a difference</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon eos rebel t1i</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 15 - 85 mm is usm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon efs 18 - 200 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nikkor 50 mm f1.2</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon 6d</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 24 -105 mm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon ef 70 -200 mm t4</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brunton 26w solar charger</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">schneider polarizer</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop cs4 &amp; cs5</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ipf 6300 print plugin for photoshop</p>\r\n about sizing\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>i have unlimited editions of everything in their folio size -\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>for larger blah blah limited editions\r\n\r\nif you can dream it - i might be able to print it!  feel free to inquire about custom sizing over and above the x - large size!  some of them go even bigger...','The Process','','inherit','open','open','','125-revision-v1','','','2013-12-08 00:09:48','2013-12-08 00:09:48','',125,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/125-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(461,2,'2013-12-08 12:41:33','2013-12-08 12:41:33','','frozenintime300608_450x300','','inherit','open','open','','frozenintime300608_450x300','','','2013-12-08 12:41:33','2013-12-08 12:41:33','',125,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/