taineer.  the purpose of the 1909 duke of abruzzi expedition was primarily to explore new terrain - even an attempt of k2 was mounted.  the photographs are reflective of this spirit - they show new and magnificent places, not of this earth, back upon the spirit of adventure &amp; exploration that was the primary objective.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/z070.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-464 alignleft\" style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; cursor: default; float: left; border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"z070\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/z070.jpg\" width=\"294\" height=\"347\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><a title=\"ansel adams\" href=\"http://en.wikipediAnsel Adams\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Ansel Adams</span></a></span>\r\n\r\nFor american nature photographers ansel adams is the photographer to which all others seem a footnote - &amp; to his credit, his technique is very democratic, the zone system outlined in his masterpiece book “the negative” being the foundation upon which my photography is based.  as a man of his time, he shot with a large format camera &amp; a tripod at f64 - f64 meaning the smallest of aperture size and thus unlimited depth of field and great sharpness and clarity to the image.  capturing detail in the nooks and crannies of ice and rock is the essence of mountain photography.  i was inspired by the way that ansel adams worked with the texture of granite cliffs, desert badlands, or adobe,the results speak for themselves:\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><a title=\"shiro shirahata\" href=\"http://www.shiro-shirahata.net/garalley.html\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Shiro Shirahata</span></a></span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">a photographer seminal to photographing just the himalayas is shiro shirahata.  his 2 folio books “nepal himalaya” &amp; “karakoram” begin to see the mountains themselves as characters - his books are portrait albums of the tallest mountains on earth.  his style represents the height of expedition style - on his treks he brought armies of porters, they hunted game, carried a Hasselblad medium format &amp; tripod.   shirahata - the culmination of expedition style</p>\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><b><b> </b></b></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><a title=\"galen rowell\" href=\" http://www.mountainlight.com/gallery.html \" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Galen Rowell</span></a></span>\r\n\r\ngalen rowell i see as an evolution to “alpine style”.  his tool of choice was the nikkor 20 mm f4 on a 35mm dslr - in other words, he could handhold the smaller, lighter, wide lensed camera, and get himself just about anywhere - a great climber in his own right with that camera.  rowell - the dawn of alpine style and the nikkor 20 mm - evolution - but still carried film  JUST AS ROWELLS TIME SAW ALPINE STYLE NOW IS\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/GalenRowell_1940-20021.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-468 alignnone\" alt=\"GalenRowell_1940-2002\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/GalenRowell_1940-20021.jpg\" width=\"290\" height=\"435\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\njust as the early siege expeditions to climb the great peaks have evolved to more lightweight attempts, we can see here that mountain photography has now paralleled the evolution of expeditions  - from larger, logistically cumbersome endeavours to a lighter \"alpine style\" - in that an individual can carry everything he needs upon his person in order to procure amazing images.  now is the era of ultralight - space age materials, solar charging, memory cards that hold 3 days of heavy shooting on something the size of a postage stamp.\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">With the digital era photography has risen like a phoenix from it’s own ashes.  there is a level of control for the photographer (and especially the home photographer) previously unknown in the art.  From photoshop, photomerging, rgb printers, high sensitivity sensors, lens stabilization -</p>\r\n\r\n<div> lens stabilization and the high sensitivities obtainable by digital sensors have made it possible now to shoot without a tripod - a seriously clunky encumbrance on uneven terrain in the mountains.  a cart full of giant photo plates has evolved to a backpack full of xray sensitive film cartridges and is now solid state media cards that you can slip in your pocket.  not to be forgotten is that everything has to get safely back from asia.</div>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>photoshopping &amp; photomerging - taking multiple photographs &amp; blending them together in photoshop - has enabled the individual photographer to produces enormous high resolution images the images are merged - the advantage being that you can them make them pretty big as the combined effect makes for a massive image possible.  merge of photographs - the photographer now has the ability to shoot overlapping sections of a scene and merge the pieces in photoshop - my giant panoramas are all explorations of this ability.- 4x 20 megapixel images will blend together into an image between just under 60 megapixels - quite a powerful tool indeed - high sensitivity sensors &amp; handheld - lens stabilization\r\n\r\nphotoshop.  rgb printers\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>baryta paper - baryllium - testing - laboriously profiled\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>homemade - hand signed (image)\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>gear i have used that has made a difference\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">i like to shoot on canon as it is the most universal and cannot accept just about any lens ever made.  they will cram a few extra megapixels onto their sensors, which i like as long as i keep the ISO below 400.  i also like the lightness and styling in the shape of the camera, which has to be carried to some difficult places and up high, where ounces of weight can really be magnified as an additional encumbrance.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">one area however where i shift the weight/performance equation is toward optics - for me i really want to shoot with high quality zooms - and hopefully one zoom to do the heavy lifting, as i have found that unmounting lenses in the himalaya inevitably invites dust onto the sensor - particularly noticeable when the lens is stopped down beyond f11, which is frequently where i am shooting.  like most photographers now, i have switched over to \"full frame\" &amp; with the upsizes off of the standard aps-c sensor it has also become necessary to add a second zoom to my kit - sad to carry the extra weight but the one area i choose not to shave ounces is with my optics.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">my gear:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon eos rebel t1i - canon efs 15-85 mm is usm</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">canon 6d - canon ef 24-105 mm &amp; canon ef 70-200 mm t4</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nikkor 50 mm f1.2 w canon mount adapter ring</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">schneider polarizer</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brunton 26w solar charger</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">my post process:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">originate in Camera Raw</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop cs4 &amp; cs5</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">ipf 6300 print plugin for photoshop</p>\r\nabout sizing\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>i have unlimited editions of everything in their folio size -\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>for larger blah blah limited editions\r\n\r\nif you can dream it - i might be able to print it!  feel free to inquire about custom sizing over and above the x - large size!  some of them go even bigger...','The Process','','inherit','open','open','','125-revision-v1','','','2013-12-08 15:38:12','2013-12-08 15:38:12','',125,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/125-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(478,2,'2013-12-08 15:38:30','2013-12-08 15:38:30','<p dir