\n<p dir=\"ltr\">brunton 26w solar charger</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">photoshop cs4 &amp; cs5 - ipf 6300 print plugin for photoshop</p>\r\nabout sizing\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>i have unlimited editions of everything in their folio size -\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>for larger blah blah limited editions\r\n\r\nif you can dream it - i might be able to print it!  feel free to inquire about custom sizing over and above the x - large size!  some of them go even bigger...\r\n\r\n</div>','The Process','','inherit','open','open','','125-revision-v1','','','2013-12-08 16:21:44','2013-12-08 16:21:44','',125,'http://dev.dougkofsky.com/125-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(498,2,'2013-12-08 16:24:06','2013-12-08 16:24:06','hard to know where to start to quantify my experience of the cross cultural adventures undertaken to put myself in position - none of it could have been done without the excellent professional services of local guides in the respective countries of nepal and pakistan.\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">within their national borders these 2 countries hold 13 of the 14 tallest peaks on earth.  because of logistical considerations i have now visited nepal on 4 occasions &amp; pakistan once.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">nepal is the hub of the himalayan tourism destination wheel, a hindu/somewhat buddhist amalgam of contradiction that starts to obtain its own logic only upon closer inspection than the patient can at times be expected to contrive.  everything starts and ends in the city of kathmandu - which once navigated is the final barrier to nirvana.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">many national parks are demarcated within nepal for trekking tourism, and there are among the locals some of the most hospitable hosts and indomitable guides in the world.  truly at present a mecca for anyone who wants to see giant mountains and accompanying culture.  tourist inflation is soaring, as globalisation adjusts prices to near western levels in tourist hotspots, in the 3rd poorest country in the world.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">But what you see here cannot help but change you.  Just everything is different.  And in a beautiful way, Nepal is so open to adventure - the feeling that with a pile of rupees in your hand &amp; a good pair of boots, you can go just about anywhere.  cheers to that.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Pakistan was a different case - the level of apprehension even at the name for americans now is steadily escalating, and the perception of that country has never been lower.  I am very lucky - I was able to visit in a period of stability during the summer of 2011 - i had put it off &amp; put it off, only to be able to take the plunge after a rought episode at work prompted a personal spell of recklessness - when i bought a plane ticket.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">best decision of my life - i loved every minute of pakistan, even when i was bitching:)  people there were so cool - present, not scamming you, open to real discussion, sad over the loss of friendship between our countries.  i met some wonderful guys &amp; pray we can turn it around.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In northern pakistan the himalayas end on the flanks of a mountain named nanga parbat.  another mountain range lies to the north of here, the karakoram range - with dimensions attaining similar magnitude in scale.  I was blessed to trek the baltoro glacier at least once, and photograph “the throne room of the mountain gods.”  The scale and architecture of these peaks is on another level - and the weather pattern in the karakoram is very different than the himalaya - with larger glaciers &amp; more instability.  for 15 days we drank water stained brown with the silty dust that rains off this similarly colored landscape.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">himalaya - \"abode of snow\" (sanskrit)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">karakoram - \"black rock\" (turkic)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">