 of many a mountaineer.  the purpose of the 1909 duke of abruzzi expedition was primarily to explore new terrain - even an attempt of k2 was mounted.  the photographs are reflective of this spirit - they show new and magnificent places, not of this earth, back upon the spirit of adventure &amp; exploration that was the primary objective.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/z070.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-464 alignleft\" style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; cursor: default; border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"z070\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/z070.jpg\" width=\"294\" height=\"347\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><a title=\"ansel adams\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia/Ansel Adams\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Ansel Adams</span></a></span></strong>\r\n\r\nFor american nature photographers ansel adams is the photographer to which all others seem a footnote - &amp; to his credit, his technique is very democratic, the zone system outlined in his masterpiece book “the negative” being the foundation upon which my photography is based.  as a man of his time, he shot with a large format camera &amp; a tripod at f64 - f64 meaning the smallest of aperture size and thus unlimited depth of field and great sharpness and clarity to the image.  capturing detail in the nooks and crannies of ice and rock is the essence of mountain photography.  i was inspired by the way that ansel adams worked with the texture of granite cliffs, desert badlands, or adobe,the results speak for themselves:\r\n<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/shiro-shirohata.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft  wp-image-486\" alt=\"shiro-shirohata\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/shiro-shirohata.jpg\" width=\"235\" height=\"338\" /> </a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Shiro Shirahata</span></strong></