 and the appearance of 80+ porters, a cook crew of 15, 3 pakistani guides, one western leader, 10 tourists, 3 goats, and a handful of chickens is bound to lead to some friendly commingling - not just with 3 lonely guys on outpost duty but with other tourist groups here from around the world to see the show.\n\ni find that expedition trekking, more expensive &amp; restrictive as opposed to the more freewheeling individual trekking, is not without certain logistical advantages.  the human to human time for tourists &amp; crew can provide a nice respite from the solitude of walking the mountains.  another advantage is  that having every logistical detail pre-arranged and dealt with in advance leaves lots of time to wander off &amp; shoot without having to worry about said detail - providing the weather cooperates - it\'s hard to put a price tag on that.\n\n&nbsp;','gore camp','','inherit','open','open','','309-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-14 18:40:25','2013-12-14 18:40:25','',309,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/309-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(519,2,'2013-12-14 17:50:05','2013-12-14 17:50:05','<p dir=\"ltr\">Coming to the himalayas was like meeting friends i had heard alot about.  Reading of the  struggles in the valleys and on the flanks, in the irrational pursuit to reach  the tops of these great mountains - these stories had inspired such vivid images in my mind, that it followed i would take the pilgrimage here as a matter of course.  My first journey was around Dhaulagiri in 2008, the seventh tallest mountain in the world.  As suddenly as we approached, newly opened eyes to this foreign landscape, as a photographer, I knew exactly what needed to be done.  I had suddenly seemed to synergize my two great loves- photography &amp; mountains.  That first trip has been followed by 4 more, each journey its own artistic &amp; technical evolution from the last.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>My dream is to photograph the great himalayan peaks - the impossible geography of ultimate m\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-112\" alt=\"doug_and_friends\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/doug_and_friends-300x200.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style: normal;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style: normal;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style: normal;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style: normal;\">ountain form.  There are 14 mountains on earth whose tops reach more than 8000 meters above sea level.   with my eyes &amp; camera i have seen &amp; photographed 10 of them.  Around these “sacred” summits lie countless other examples of mountain architecture, in distillations approaching perfection - what i am looking for - the most beautiful mountains in the world.</span></span></span></span>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<a title=\"The Gallery\" href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/gallery/\">View the Gallery</a>','<span class=\"small\">About</span><br />Doug Kofsky','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2013-12-14 17:50:05','2013-12-14 17:50:05','',86,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(520,2,'2013-12-14 17:51:56','2013-12-14 17:51:56','<p dir=\"ltr\">Coming to the himalayas was like meeting friends i had heard alot about.  Reading of the  struggles in the valleys and on the flanks, in the irrational pursuit to reach  the tops of these great mountains - these stories had inspired such vivid images in my mind, that it followed i would take the pilgrimage here as a matter of course.  My first journey was around Dhaulagiri in 2008, the seventh tallest mountain in the world.  As suddenly as we approached, newly opened eyes to this foreign landscape, as a photographer, I knew exactly what needed to be done.  I had suddenly seemed to synergize my two great loves- photography &amp; mountains.  That first trip has been followed by 4 more, each journey its own artistic &amp; technica