14 18:27:47','2013-12-14 18:27:47','hard to know where to start to quantify my experience of the cross cultural adventures undertaken to put myself in position - none of it could have been done without the excellent professional services of local guides in the respective countries of nepal and pakistan.  within their national borders these 2 countries hold 13 of the 14 tallest peaks on earth.  because of logistical considerations i have now visited nepal on 4 occasions &amp; pakistan once.\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>nepal is the hub of the himalayan tourism destination wheel, a hindu/somewhat buddhist amalgam of contradiction that starts to obtain its own logic only upon closer inspection than the patient can at times be expected to contrive.  everything starts and ends in the city of kathmandu - which once navigated is the final barrier to nirvana.  many national parks are demarcated within nepal for trekking tourism, and there are among the locals some of the most hospitable hosts and indomitable guides in the world.  truly at present a mecca for anyone who wants to see giant mountains and accompanying culture.  tourist inflation is soaring, as globalisation adjusts prices to near western levels in tourist hotspots, in the 3rd poorest country in the world.But what you see here cannot help but change you.  Just everything is different.  And in a beautiful way, Nepal is so open to adventure - the feeling that with a pile of rupees in your hand &amp; a good pair of boots, you can go just about anywhere.  cheers to that.\r\n\r\nPakistan was a different case - the level of apprehension even at the name for americans now is steadily escalating, and the perception of that country has never been lower.  I am very lucky - I was able to visit in a period of stability during the summer of 2011 - i had put it off &amp; put it off, only to be able to take the plunge after a rought episode at work prompted a personal spell of recklessness - when i bought a plane ticket.  best decision of my life - i loved every minute of pakistan, even when i was bitching:)  people there were so cool - present, not scamming you, open to real discussion, sad over the loss of friendship between our countries.  i met some wonderful guys &amp; pray we can turn it around.\r\n\r\n<b><b> </b></b>In northern pakistan the himalayas end on the flanks of a mountain named nanga parbat.  another mountain range lies to the north of here, the karakoram range - with dimensions attaining similar magnitude in scale.  I was blessed to trek the baltoro glacier at least once, and photograph “the throne room of the mountain gods.”  The scale and architecture of these peaks is on another level - and the weather pattern in the karakoram is very different than the himalaya - with larger glaciers &amp; more instability.  for 15 days we drank water stained brown with the silty dust that rains off this similarly colored landscape.\r\n\r\n<span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;\">Section Title</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Location','','inherit','open','open','','88-revision-v1','','','2013-12-14 18:27:47','2013-12-14 18:27:47','',88,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/88-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(525,2,'2013-12-14 18:48:37','2013-12-14 18:48:37','<strong>From Urdukas Camp</strong>\n\nthese are the fabled great trango towers, with the sun setting and clouds swirling around them.  they are unique in shape, scope, awesomeness, and aesthetic to me in just about every way.  they are testpieces of alpinism.  while i will never stand on top of any of their extremely dangerous summits, i am glad to have seen such an ideal in my mountain journeys.  i am comforted that such places exist to feed a truth that i feel in my soul.\n\n&nbsp;','trango sunset','','inherit','open','open','','370-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-14 18:48:37','2013-12-14 18:48:37','',370,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/370-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(526,2,'2013-12-14 19:08:47','2013-12-14 19:08:47','<strong>From Muldea Viewpoint - Annapurna Himalaya, Nepal</strong>\n\nmuldea view lies within new trekking territory developing in the southwestern foothills of the annapurna himalaya.  the area is already world renowned for nearby poon hill and annapurna basecamp, and muldea only enhances the cornucopia of awesomeness this region has to offer for variety of amazing places to see.  from the viewpoint new vantages of annapurna south, fishtail, and dhaulagiri are visible.\n\na lovely gurung couple and their amazing son run a guesthouse in the outpost of dobato, lying below, which serves as the base for the climb of muldea, and lies as well within the tradition of impeccable gurung hospitality chara annapurna region, radhav gurung and his wife and son ho.  radhav was also kind enough to show me a shortcut across the range to the east for my proposed crossing through rhododendron country in that direction.','Dhaulagiri I (8167 m)','','inherit','open','open','','307-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-14 19:08:47','2013-12-14 19:08:47','',307,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/307-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(527,2,'2013-12-15 14:50:35','2013-12-15 14:50:35','<strong>From the Baltoro Glacier - Karakoram Range, Pakistan</strong>\n\nstopped here on our way back down in perfect weather - all the time in the world to contemplate the lovely trango towers reflected in a small pool in the texture of the glacier.  i am indebted to the superb photographer michael anderson, a contemporary, for hi','trango reflections from urdukas','','inherit','open','open','','360-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-15 14:50:35','2013-12-15 14:50:35','',360,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/360-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(528,2,'2013-12-15 15:55:14','2013-12-15 15:55:14','<strong>From Gore Camp</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>one of my primary objectives for this trek was to document alpenglow on \"the shining wall\" - the west face of gasherbrum IV (7912m).  i was lucky with weather this night and really could just spend an evening together with this geometrically perfect icon of the baltoro mustagh - the subrange of the karakoram where the mountains attain similar scale to the high himalaya yet their architecture is bolder, with sharper angles cleaved from a sterner cloth.  this combination results in what to me stands symbolically as the profoundest mountain range on earth.','dusk on the gasherbrum massif','','inherit','open','open','','320-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-15 15:55:14','2013-12-15 15:55:14','',320,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/320-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(529,2,'2013-12-15 16:30:34','2013-12-15 16:30:34','<strong>From the Trek Around Manaslu - Nepal</strong>\n\nthis is from early on, around manaslu with purna and ramesh as a team for the first time.  we were quite low down, it was early in the trek, and i saw the river framed this way between the two steep hills, and i wanted to line things up just so with the vegetation.  it took a little wiggling around off the trail this way and that, til i found a small clearing where everything looked just right.  got the shot and then found them up ahead, confused and concerned a tiger might have gotten me.\n\nwater that drains off of the himalaya, north or south, must eventually flow south in order to obey gravity downward toward the indian ocean.  the rivers to the north of the range must cut their way through, and the result is the incredible relief in the gorges they make.  from here we are still quite low down, yet nearby lies terrain above 8000 meters.  this is so amazing about nepal - the relief of the south side and the scale of the vistas, as well as the accomodating climate of the relative lowlands in the south. sunny day wearing a t-shirt.  we eventually followed the river up and around the range to the north - of course quite a different story &amp; the end of t-shirt weather indeed.\n\n&nbsp;','budhi gandaki river','','inherit','open','open','','263-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-15 16:30:34','2013-12-15 16:30:34','',263,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/263-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(530,2,'2013-12-15 17:12:27','2013-12-15 17:12:27','<strong>Karakoram Range, Pakistan</strong>\n\na 2 minute opening of opportunity in 3 days of storm, a small window opened in the clouds  - sun and window aligning paths momentarily in their trajectories, and a beam of light on the trango group across the valley from where i stood on the hillside above urdukas.\n\nthe sunlight reveals the south and east wall of great trango (6286m), a wall in the running for the title of most precipitous cliff in the world.  next to it, also bathed in morning light, is nameless tower.\n\n&nbsp;','great trango & nameless tower','','inherit','open','open','','318-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-15 17:12:27','2013-12-15 17:12:27','',318,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/318-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(531,2,'2013-12-15 17:56:11','2013-12-15 17:56:11','<strong>Nepal Himalaya</strong>\n\ndelightful day hike with purna and ramesh up the hill above the village of samdo to attain perspective on the manaslu himalaya lying across the upper valley.  this day found ramesh bahadur in fine form running up and down the mountain, and the coinage of the term huin ko bag - \"snow tiger\" - the kid is gifted in the mountains.\n\nnorth of the range here, and quite close to the border of tibet.  the budhi gandaki descends to the left, which we have followed up, and will now be departing from to ascend the larkya la, in the right center, a 5000 meter pass that is the high point of our circle around manaslu.  tucked away out of sight beneath the hill we are standing on is samdo, the last of the tibetan villages on the north side before the crossing.\n\nat least 3 different passes over the border nearby and yaks being herded up and sent over by traders and other men with teams of horses endlessly coming and going in their caravans.  it is also a crossroads for tourists, for you must get over the larkya la in order to avoid a long trip back down the budhi gandaki.  so different than the south side, more buddhist than hindu, with different weather, vegetation, people, every\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_278\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"586\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_samdo_ri_sample.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-278  \" alt=\"from_samdo_ri_sample\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_samdo_ri_sample.jpg\" width=\"586\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','manaslu himalaya from samdo ri','','inherit','open','open','','288-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-15 17:56:11','2013-12-15 17:56:11','',288,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/288-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(532,2,'2013-12-15 19:26:36','2013-12-15 19:26:36','<strong>Langtang Himalaya, Nepal</strong>\n\npangsang lek was an unexplored area i had scouted via map and line of sight from my journey into the langtang valley.  it looked like a good place to get up above the trees for a look at the ganesh himalaya across the valley to the west, as well as perhaps a closer inspection of the flanks of the langtang group.  after some adventures avoiding overzealous would be guides disguised as drunken sherpas i finally found an oasis at the hotel of kanji tamang sherpa, in the village of khanjim.\n\ni\'d set out in the dark to get here as usual, and the terrain was high kharkas, seasonal grazing for the animals, abandoned at this time of year, which was winter.  in my pocket i carried yak cheese i had bought and fresh bread baked below by my lovely hostess, rolling it with her hands at the edge of the fire while we smoked there and hung out the night before in the village.\n\nupon my return back down i was lucky enough to get smashed at a rollicking tibetan ceremony that culminated in running around the house barefoot with burning wax figures.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_267\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"562\"]<a href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_pangsang_lek_SAMPLE.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-267  \" alt=\"from_pangsang_lek_SAMPLE\" src=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/content/uploads/2013/11/from_pangsang_lek_SAMPLE.jpg\" width=\"562\" height=\"396\" /></a> detail[/caption]','from pangsang lek','','inherit','open','open','','265-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-15 19:26:36','2013-12-15 19:26:36','',265,'http://162.243.233.67/dougkofsky/265-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(535,2,'2013-12-16 15:33:37','2013-12-16 15:33:37','<p dir=\"ltr\">Coming to the himalayas was like meeting friends i had heard alot about.  Reading of the  struggles in the valleys and on the flanks, in the irrational pursuit to reach  the tops of these great mountains - these stories had inspired such vivid images in my mind, that it followed i would take the pilgrimage here as a matter of course.  My first journey was around Dhaulagiri in 2008, the seventh tallest mountain in the world.  As suddenly as we approached, newly opened eyes to this foreign landscape, as a photographer, I knew exactly what needed to be done.  I had suddenly seemed to synergize my two great loves- photography &amp; mountains.  That first trip has been followed by 4 more, each journey its own artistic &amp; technical evolution from the last.</p>\r\n<b><b> </b></b>My dream is to photograph the great himalayan peaks - the impossible geography of ultimate mountain form.  There are 14 mountains on earth whose tops reach more than 8000 meters above sea level.   with my eyes &amp; camera i have seen &amp; photographed 10 of them.  Around these “sacred” summits lie countless other examples of mountain architecture, in distillations approaching perfection - what i am looking for - the most beautiful mountains in the world.\r\n<div> <a title=\"The Gallery\" href=\"http://dev.dougkofsky.com/gallery/\">View the Gallery</a></div>','<span class=\"small\">About</span><br />Doug Kofsky','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2013-12-16 