 tourism, and there are among the locals some of the most hospitable hosts and indomitable guides in the world.  truly at present a mecca for anyone who wants to see giant mountains.  tourist inflation is soaring, as globalisation adjusts prices to near western levels in tourist hotspots, here in what is known as the 3rd poorest country in the world. But what you see here cannot help but change you.  Just everything is different.  And in a beautiful way. Nepal is open for true adventure - the feeling that with a pile of rupees in your hand &amp; a good pair of boots, you can go just about anywhere.  cheers to that.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Pakistan</span></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Pakistan - the level of apprehension even at the name for americans now is steadily escalating, and the perception of that country has never been lower.  I am very lucky - I was able to visit in a period of stability during the summer of 2011 - my dream was to see k2 and surrounds, and i had put it off as too risky, again and again, only to be able to take the plunge after a rought episode at work prompted a personal spell of recklessness - when i bought a plane ticket.  best decision of my life - i loved so much about pakistan - so many cool people - good, honest, intelligent people  - present, not scamming you, open to real discussion, sad over the loss of friendship between our countries.  i met some wonderful guys &amp; pray we can turn it around.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> In northern pakistan the himalayas end on the flanks of a mountain named nanga parbat.  another mountain range lies to the north of here, the karakoram range - with dimensions attaining similar magnitude in scale.  I was blessed to trek the baltoro glacier at least once, and photograph “the throne room of the mountain gods.”  The scale and architecture of these peaks is on another level - and the weather pattern in the karakoram is very different than the himala